<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Patrols in Belfast to be Halted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- All Army patrols will be
removed from Northern Irish capital Belfast at the weekend because
of the reduced threat of terrorism, a senior police officer said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Royal Ulster Constabulary Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan said
the move would "undoubtedly have an impact on troop levels" in
Northern Ireland, and he hoped to move "as quickly as possible" to
remove all patrols.
</P>
<P>
"After this weekend we will be returning to the position where
there will be no military patrols in the greater Belfast area," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But for the time being, security will remain tight along the
border with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very welcome development and it is made possible by
the fact that we are continuing to have a significantly reduced
terrorist threat," Flanagan explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of soldiers in the province was under
review. But he denied that the latest move was meant to encourage
weapons decommissioning by paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no trade-off," he said. "I have a duty to care
and protect the people." Groups that were holding on to their
arsenals were "a potent threat" to the peace process, he added.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland First Minister David Trimble and Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams held their face-to-face talks on Thursday,
the first direct encounter between Irish republican and
pro-British unionist leaders since 1922, marking a milestone in
the search for peace in the troubled British province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
