<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Opposition MP Grilled on Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lankan Opposition
Member of Parliament belonging to the United National Party (UNP)
Wednesday evening was grilled by the Criminal Investigation's
Department on an alleged conspiracy to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
Jayalath Jayawardena is reported to have had a clandestine
meeting with the political leader of the Tamil rebels, Thamil
Chelvam, in a Vavuniya jungle hideout of the rebel tigers in June
this year.
</P>
<P>
They are alleged to have discussed a plan to topple the
government. A Tamil driver who had taken Jayawardena to the
location for the meeting was arrested earlier, official Daily News
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police sources were quoted as saying that Jayawardena had
violated Defense Ministry regulations which requires a person to
give the location of a terrorist or a group of terrorists if he
had knowledge of the same.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga revealed at a convention in
Kurunegala District Tuesday that the subject of the discussions
between Jayawardena and Thamil Chelvam was a plan to topple the
government.
</P>
<P>
She also alleged that both the UNP and the Tamil rebels
demanded the government to talk unconditionally with the "Tigers"
soon after this secret meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war against the
government since 1983 for a separate state in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Commander Says More Troops Could Have </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Marines Corps
Commander Major General Suharto Wednesday said they did not have
enough troops to cover every corner of Jakarta to safeguard the
capital during the rioting and burning in May.
</P>
<P>
The commander told the Joint Fact-Finding Team investigating
the riots that 31 companies, 3,100 troops in total, could easily
vanish in a city as large as this one, the Indonesian Observer
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 31 companies, 11 had been shipped from the Marine's
naval base in Surabaya in East Java, and the remainder were
supplied by Jakarta's own base.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters following a session with members of the
team, Suharto said his men had been on alert since May 6.
</P>
<P>
"I am just glad that my men did their best while carrying out
their job. However, I do not agree we were told about the riots
too late to prevent it from happening. I think if we had enough
forces at that time, it would not have been too late to react," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government established the Joint Fact-Finding Team in July
to investigate reports that the May riots in Jakarta and other
cities, which left 1,200 people dead, were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Suharto told reporters that he had no knowledge nor had
received information from his men concerning the theory of "an
engineered riot."
</P>
<P>
"I personally have no information of that issue and neither do
any of my men. I think that would be the part of the affairs of
(the armed forces) intelligence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Suharto will be the sixth prominent government official to be
questioned by the team, following former Jakarta Regional Military
commander Major General Sjafrie, Jakarta's Governor Sutiyoso,
former Jakarta Police chief Major General Hamami Nata, Chief of
the Armed Forces' intelligence unit Major General Zacky Anwar
Makarim and former chief of the Army's Strategic Reserve Command
Prabowo Subianto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
