<HEADLINE> Britain Supports New U.N. Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain Thursday expressed its
support to the U.N Security Council's new resolution on suspending
its periodic review of sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council resolution, which was unanimously passed
Wednesday, was designed to punish Iraq for announcing last month
it would no longer cooperate with the UN weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett said in a
statement issued early Thursday: "This new resolution sends a
strong and united signal to Iraq that its tactics are
counterproductive."
</P>
<P>
"The move is a further response to Iraq's unilateral decision
on 5 August to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM (United Nations
Special Commission on Iraq)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett noted the Iraqi government had only delayed the moment
when the sanctions could be lifted and Britain would not support a
partial lifting of sanctions in exchange for Baghdad's partial
compliance with U.N. resolutions on giving up the weapons.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that the British government would not
rule out the possibility of using force as a possible option to
ensure the implementation of UN resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
