<HEADLINE> Mandela Urged to Release Lesotho Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela should immediately release the three-nation
commission report on the alleged electoral fraud in Lesotho, the
country's opposition alliance said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela should note that the Basotho people had waited far too
long for the results of the commission's probe and there was no
need for it to be tabled first at a meeting of Southern African
Development Community (SADC) heads of state in Mauritius, South
African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Basotho National Party
leader Everestus Sekhonyane as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We want South Africa, especially President Nelson Mandela, as
our only neighbor, to consider our plea.
</P>
<P>
"This (The report) has got nothing to do with Mauritius, even
(Zimbabwean President) Robert Mugabe," Sekhonyane said, referring
to South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's announcement
Wednesday night that the report would first be handed over to
Mandela, Mugabe and Botswana President Festus Mogae.
</P>
<P>
An earlier proposal that the report should be tabled first to
SADC summit in Mauritius on September 13-14, before being made
public, was rejected by the opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
Sekhonyane said that the opposition had invited South Africa
to investigate their complaint that the May 23 general election
was rigged to favor the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy,
which won with a landslide.
</P>
<P>
"They have done so. They have seen the report. Now we should
be the next group to see it, not people somewhere in Mauritius,
who have nothing to do with our situation."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki and his SADC troika colleagues on Lesotho -- Botswana
Foreign Minister Mompati Merafhe and Zimbabwe's envoy to Maseru
Nelson Moyo -- held a series of meetings with Lesotho government
and opposition parties about the report on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki announced that the troika would not make the report
public as expected, but wanted to table it at the SADC meeting
first.
</P>
<P>
This evoked objections from the opposition, leading to a
compromise that the report plus the responses from all stake
holders would be handed to the presidents of South Africa,
Zimbabwe and Botswana, who would then make a decision on the way
forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
