<HEADLINE> Malaysia's UMNO Youth Chief Refuses to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ruling United
Malays National Organization (UMNO) Youth chief Ahmad Zahid Hamidi
said Thursday that he will not resign from the post and will leave
it to the UMNO Supreme Council to decide his position in the
movement.
</P>
<P>
A special meeting of the UMNO Youth executive committee here
Thursday unanimously resolved that his position in the movement be
decided by party president Mahathir Mohamad who is the country's
prime minister, Ahmad Zahid told reporters at a brief press
conference after chairing a five-hour meeting of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Zahid is known as a strong supporter of former Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim who was ousted
from the cabinet and expelled from UMNO of which he was the deputy
president last week.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Zahid had earlier been pressured by UMNO Youth leaders
from the state and divisional levels "to resign honorably" for
failing to express the movement's support for Anwar's expulsion
and for being frequently in the former deputy prime minister's
house.
</P>
<P>
"They cannot force me to resign, I will not resign from the
post," Ahmad Zahid said, adding that he would not step down as he
was elected by the delegates and in line with the UMNO
constitution and regulations he could not be dismissed from the
post.
</P>
<P>
"If any among the committee members are not happy with my
remaining as head of the movement, then they will have to wait for
the party president to make a decision on my position," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
