<HEADLINE> DPRK Says Progress Made in Talks With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) said on Thursday that agreement has been
reached on some issue with the United States in recent high-level
talks.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by a DPRK Foreign Ministry spokesman
when commenting on the latest round of DPRK-U.S. talks concluded
in New York last week.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the United States admitted its failure to
fulfil the program of light water reactor project and supply of
heavy oil.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. promised to begin the supply of heavy oil due
for this year in late September and complete it by the end of the
year, enter into light water reactor project in real earnest from
November, hold negotiations for deleting the DPRK from the list of
"terrorism sponsor nations" and lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He also said the U.S. promised to take positive measures for
continued humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two sides have also reached an agreement
in a package form on mutual pending issues such as the four-party
talks and the missile talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman defended DPRK's launching of a satellite on
August 31, saying that the development, launch and use of
satellites were internationally-recognized rights of a state with
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He said at the talks the DPRK side made it clear that in case
the U.S. takes a step backward again, the DPRK will take practical
measures to show that it can not unilaterally sacrifice its own
nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the DPRk will watch how the U.S. side
implements the agreement in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
