<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Palestinians' Support for Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of Palestinians
supporting the peace process and the Oslo Accords declined, said a
public opinion poll released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by the Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center (JMCC) by the end of August, said the decline in support
shown this year is a departure from the first four years of Oslo,
when the Palestinian public showed consistent support for the
Palestinian-Israeli peace process despite sudden and dramatic
political and economic changes.
</P>
<P>
The negative trend can be measured through three main
indicators of the poll: support for Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, his faction Fatah and the peace process itself.
</P>
<P>
In a poll conducted by JMCC in December 1996, 78.1 percent of
Palestinians surveyed showed support for the peace process, and
now only 55.6 Palestinians expressed strong or lukewarm support.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was considered in the poll of December 1996 the most
trusted politician by 42 percent Palestinians surveyed and now the
percentage has declined to 32.6 in the new poll, while Fatah's
support declined from 42 percent to the present 34.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, 68.6 percent of the newly surveyed Palestinians were
still optimistic about peace, while 29.7 percent were pessimistic,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted among 1,192 Palestinians over the age of
18, with 757 from the West Bank and others from Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Canada to Restore Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Diplomatic relations between
Nigeria and Canada will be fully restored in October when both
countries reopen their high commissions, Nigerian Foreign
Minister Ignatius Olisemeka said.
</P>
<P>
After a closed door meeting with the visiting Canadian
Secretary of State for Latin America and Africa David Kilgour in
Abuja Wednesday, the minister said, "by mid October, the Nigerian
mission in Ottawa, Canada, will be full of activities."
</P>
<P>
Kilgour who arrived here last Sunday told reporters In capital
Abuja that Canada "is now prepared to go into full bilateral
relations with Nigeria by mid October this year."
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic relations between the two countries were
severed in 1995 when Canada closed its embassy in Lagos
following the hanging of nine minority rights activists on
November 10, 1995 by the then Sani Abacha government.
</P>
<P>
Alleged human rights abuses by the late Gen. Abacha regime led
to a spate of international sanctions against Nigeria including
the suspension of Nigeria's membership from the Commonwealth of
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations with South Africa, Britain and United
States also went sour in 1996 when the Abacha government
rationalized the human rights abuses in the West African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
