<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila Allies Get Tough Despite Truce Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Allies of Congolese
President Laurent Kabila have vowed they will not withdraw their
troops from the country until Rwanda and Uganda have done so
first, it was reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, which sent troops to Congo (K)
to help Kabila stop a Tutsi-led rebellion, made the vow despite a
cease-fire agreement they were party to earlier this week,
reported South African Press Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
"We can't be cheated and lured into a withdrawal. We will do
it on a reciprocal basis, depending on the situation," Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe was quoted as telling a Zimbabwean weekly
magazine released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Financial Gazette quoted Mugabe as saying that
Angolan President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos and Namibian President
Sam Nujoma agreed with Mugabe that their forces would only leave
once Congo was cleared of all foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
"Until we reach an agreement with the government of Congo, we
will remain there," Dos Santos was quoted as saying. "So we will
be there until the withdrawal of invading foreign troops."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also quoted Zimbabwean Defense Force commander
General Vitalis Zvinavashe as saying the war would intensify if
the rebels and their backers did not observe the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The hardening of attitudes by the three southern African
governments came only two days after Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia
agreed with rebel allies Uganda and Rwanda on a provisional
cease-fire and withdrawal of foreign troops from Congo.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced Tuesday by Zambia's President
Frederick Chiluba, who chaired a two-day summit at Victoria
Falls, Zimbabwe, aimed at resolving the conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Uganda and Rwanda were at Victoria Falls for
the summit, but a delegation of Congolese rebels was not allowed
to participate in the meeting. The rebels then declared they
would not observe the provisional cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda have consistently denied they have had
anything to do with the fighting, and dismissed Zimbabwean claims
that hundreds of their soldiers have been captured.
</P>
<P>
But Mugabe said in the report: "We have evidence, we can give
you tapes on them."
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda is just afraid to admit it has troops there but they
are the ones with more troops in Congo than anyone else," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministers and army commanders from all six countries
involved in the Congo conflict were meeting Thursday at the
Organization of African Unity headquarters in Addis Ababa in
Ethiopia to draft a plan for the cessation of fighting and the
withdrawal of all foreign troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
