<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-10 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Targets 4 Percent Economic Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus expects a 4 percent
economic growth in 1999 despite a grim global situation, Finance
Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a Cabinet meeting which approved the 1999 state
budget, Christodoulou described the prospects for Cyprus' economic
growth in 1999 as "encouraging".
</P>
<P>
"The rate of economic growth is expected to reach 4 percent in
real terms, despite the increasingly difficult outside environment
because of the financial crisis in Asia and Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Unemployment is expected to be maintained at around 3
percent and the inflation rate at 2.5 to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The rate of growth is satisfactory and if there are no
unexpected outside or domestic developments, the local economy in
1998 and 1999 will be very satisfactory," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The newly approved 1999 state budget includes 1,106.3 million
Cyprus pounds (about 2212.6 million U.S. dollars) of net revenue,
1,687.1 million pounds (about 3374.2 million dollars) of net
expenditure, and a fiscal deficit of 580.8 million pounds (about
1161.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou explained that the fiscal deficit is expected to
rise by 6.7 percent next year due primarily to the loss of some
295 million pounds (about 590 million dollars) in the past two
years in customs income because of the implementation of the
customs union agreement with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Referring to the value added tax (VAT), Christodoulou said the
VAT in EU member states must be at least 15 percent while Cyprus
currently is imposing a ceiling of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The VAT increase must be introduced gradually, he added.
</P>
<P>
The budget will be presented to the House of Representatives
for final approval by the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
