<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma May Back Primakov's PM Candidacy Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, is expected to back acting Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov's candidacy for prime minister in a hearing on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party, Agrarians and People's Power, three
leftist factions that compose the Duma's largest voting block,
will all vote in favor of the Kremlin's new choice to head the
Russian cabinet, the Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The three groups compose 213 of the Duma's deputies. Primakov
needs to get 226 votes of support from parliament's 450 lawmakers
to win Friday's confirmation hearing.
</P>
<P>
Yevgeny Primakov, a career diplomat transferred from the press
whose service spanned the Soviet and Russian times, emerged as a
possible compromise candidate last week when leftists and liberals
in the opposition-dominated State Duma put his name forward.
</P>
<P>
The Duma had twice rejected acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, Russian President Boris Yeltsin's first choice for
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting Thursday with Chernomyrdin and Yuri
Maslyukov, a Communist deputy in the Duma, Yeltsin sent a letter
to the Duma nominating acting Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov
for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Russian Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said: "Yevgeny
Primakov is a consolidating figure in the conditions where all is
heated to the limit."
</P>
<P>
He said that Primakov is a well-known politician in the
country and abroad, capable of pursuing and defending national
interests.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the liberal Yabloko movement Grigory Yavlinsky said
that Yeltsin's decision "will help stop the political crisis," and
that "it is the first instance when an open proposal was supported
by the president."
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Our Home is Russia faction Alexander Shokhin also
expressed support of Primakov's candidacy for prime minister,
calling him "an equally distant politician."
</P>
<P>
"Primakov is a politician equally distant from all political
forces, therefore he can be entrusted with forming a government,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the only opposing voice came from the faction of the
Liberal Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR).
</P>
<P>
LDPR faction leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky told a press
conference that his party will vote against Primakov's candidacy
for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He said Primakov would not be able to cope with the tasks which
would be assigned to him now in such a complex economic and social
situation.
</P>
<P>
The Primakov's government will be a "death squad" which will
act just for two months, he said.
</P>
<P>
"By supporting Yeltsin's nomination the Duma Communists will
give up on voting on non-confidence in the government and the
impeachment procedure against Yeltsin," he said. He warned that he
will raise the non-confidence issue in two months.
</P>
<P>
Born in Kiev on October 29, 1929, Primakov was graduated from
the Moscow Institute of Oriental Studies in 1953.
</P>
<P>
Once a correspondent for the national daily Pravda, an official
newspaper of the Soviet Communist Party Central Committee,
Primakov was appointed director of the Central Intelligence
Service of the Soviet Union on November 6, 1991. He has been
serving as Russian foreign minister since January 9, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
