<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Asks for Mandate Extension for MONUA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday put forward a proposal for the extension of
the mandate of the United Nations Observer Mission in Angola
(MONUA).
</P>
<P>
"I propose that the mandate of MONUA be extended until January
31, 1999." he said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal came as Annan presented to the Security Council
his report on the MONUA. The 15-member Security Council held
informal consultations here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If the warring parties in Angola have made no "substantial
progress towards the full compliance" of the Lusaka Protocol by
November, the Security Council should "take the necessary action,"
and the reduction of the MONUA would be accelerated with a view to
closing it down by early February 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the MONUA would be allowed to carry out its mandate if
the concerned parties have made decisive progress by the end of
November, when the Security Council is expected to conduct a
comprehensive view on the situation in Angola before any relevant
decision, he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan produced his report following recent reports of renewed
armed clashes in the southern African nation. The Angolian
police force killed 27 UNITA fighters in several clashes with
the rebel faction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
