<HEADLINE> Primakov Asserts Russian Status, Blasts NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia's premier-designate
Yevgeny Primakov on Thursday reiterated Moscow's opposition to
NATO expansion, saying it could lead to new polarization and
dis-stabilize international relations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 100th Conference of the Inter-Parliamentary
Union, Primakov, speaking as foreign minister, said NATO
enlargement is threatening to erect new division lines in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Primakov was nominated prime minister by Russian President
Boris Yeltsin just hours before he delivered the address in the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Participants to the 100th IPU Conference have withnessed their
hosts struggling against an economic and political crisis that
left the country without a fully functioning government for over
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, Primakov told the world parliamentarians that despite
the crisis, Russia remains a major player on the international
arena.
</P>
<P>
"Without active participation of Russia, even temporarily
feeble internally, it's not possible at all to address global
issues, to alleviate and eliminate threats which are still out
there," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia stands ready to present to the democratic and civilized
development of the world its entire foreign policy potentials,
especially its geo-political location and the influences
accumulated over the years and the status as a permanent member of
the U.N. Security Council," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted Russia's scientific and technological potentials.
</P>
<P>
The IPU conference, which officially opened Monday, is
scheduled to be concluded Friday. 
</P>
