<HEADLINE> Iran Holds Taliban, Pakistan Responsible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran stated on Thursday that
the Afghan Taliban militia and its supporter Pakistan are
responsible for the killing of Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the state-run television, the Iranian Foreign
Ministry issued a statement after a Taliban spokesman announced
that the group has found the bodies of nine Iranian diplomats
missing since August 8.
</P>
<P>
The six-point statement said the Taliban and Pakistan had
offered assurance to Iran about the safety of Iranian diplomats
before the fall of Mazari Sharif, a town in northern Afghanistan,
to the hands of the Taliban on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Iran believed that 11 diplomats of the Iranian consulate in
Mazari Sharif and a reporter of the Iranian official news agency
IRNA were kidnaped by the Taliban and transferred to unknown place.
</P>
<P>
A Taliban spokesman announced on Thursday that bodies of nine
Iranian diplomats were found but the fate of two others were
unclear so far.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban is responsible to deliver the bodies of the killed
Iranian diplomats to Iran as soon as possible, the Iranian Foreign
Ministry statement said, adding the group is also responsible to
arrest and punish those who were responsible for the killing.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the Taliban to release all the Iranians who
were kidnaped by the Afghan group when they were on the duty to
dispatch humanitarian assistance to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that more than 80 Iranian truck drivers
and aid workers were held in prisons of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The statement also stressed that Iran has the right to defend
the rights of Iranian nation against foreign aggression and the
Taliban and their supporters should take responsibility for the
consequences of Taliban's behavior.
</P>
<P>
It also called the international community, the United Nations
in particular, to carry out their duty towards the Taliban's
crimes which were an obvious violation of international laws.
</P>
<P>
The statement came at a time when rumors widely spread here
that Iran, that has established its military buildup along its
border with Afghanistan, has been prepared to launch a military
strike on Taliban's targets.
</P>
<P>
Following the grand military maneuver of the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps on the northeastern border early this
month, Iran's army on Thursday also announced to launch a large
war game along the eastern border with Afghanistan. 
</P>
