<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Says Agreement Possible as Ross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
said Thursday that an Israeli-Palestinian deal on the West Bank
redeployment is possible as U.S. envoy Dennis Ross continues his
mediation.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Netanyahu, said Ross'
decision to extend his stay here is a sign that positive results
could be produced. He believed that an agreement over the Israeli
redeployment could be reached during Ross' visit.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly hope so, and there is no reason we should not
(reach an agreement), particularly since Israel has agreed in
principle to consider the 13.1 percent withdrawal which is the
only requirement in the American initiative which applies to
Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here Wednesday afternoon on a renewed mission to
broker a deal between Israel and the Palestinians over the overdue
Israeli second stage troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Top on his agenda is the U.S. initiative put forward in January
that calls for a 13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal. The Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) has already adopted the plan, but Israel
originally rejected it, and then accepted it with certain
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Israel is demanding that the PNA agree to turn 3 percent of the
proposed land into a nature reserve where Israel retains full
security control and the Palestinians are not allowed to build.
</P>
<P>
The PNA reportedly only agreed to accept temporary limitations
and wanted to obtain an Israeli promise that the PNA could finally
gain total control over the designated area.
</P>
<P>
Ross has held talks with PNA President Yasser Arafat Wednesday
night in the West Bank city Ramallah and with Netanyahu and
Israeli President Ezer Weizman Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Weizman, Ross said he found that
both Israel and the PNA are ready to find a way to move
forward. But he added that there are still many issues to be
sorted out.
</P>
<P>
Ross is expected to meet again with Netanyahu and senior
Israeli ministers within the Inner Cabinet on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Cabinet, or Kitchen Cabinet, is in charge of the top
security issues in the Jewish state. Its members include
Netanyahu, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Minister of Industry and
Trade Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat reiterated Wednesday
night after the Arafat-Ross meeting that the PNA rejected the
Israeli changes to the U.S. initiative and is awaiting a positive
response by Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Bar-Illan urged the PNA to implement the requirements in
the U.S. proposal, including abolishing clauses in the Palestinian
Covenant calling for Israel's destruction and taking tougher
measures to fight terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
