<HEADLINE> 7 Defense Ministers Meet in Ethiopia on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Defense Ministers of
seven southern African countries met here Thursday afternoon
to discuss the conflict in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
In his remarks made at the opening session, OAU Secretary
General Salim Ahmed Salim stated that he was pleased with the
spirit of the second Victoria Falls summit which stressed the
fact that whatever the cause of the present dispute in Congo, the
time is now propitious for its settlement.
</P>
<P>
''Such a settlement should be comprehensive enough to address
the legitimate concerns of all the parties involved and whose
paramount objective would be to end the conflict, to bring the
Congolese people together in peace, unity and cohesion and to
promote a climate of understanding, harmony and cooperation in
the region,'' Salim stressed.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, ''the Organization of African Unity (OAU), working
closely with the United Nations, will continue to do its utmost
to promote a peaceful solution to the conflict in the Democratic
Republic of Congo.''
</P>
<P>
''Indeed, we do attach the greatest important to the peace,
unity, stability and territorial integrity of the Democratic
Republic of Congo as we seek to promote conditions for durable
peace, unity and stability in the Great Lakes region,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
C.M. Sampa, Zambian Minister of Defense, said the second
Victoria Falls summit gave mandate this meeting to establish the
modalities for effecting an immediate cease-fire and a mechanism
for monitoring compliance with the cease-fire provisions,
especially those relating to the withdrawal of foreign forces
from Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
He explained that the mandate is threefold: to establish the
modalities for effecting an immediate cease-fire; to establish a
mechanism for monitoring compliance with the cease-fire
provisions; and the withdrawal of foreign forces from the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the session, Berhanu Dinka, U.N. representative to
the Great Lakes region, assured U.N.'s continued concern and
commitment to assist in every possible way to contribute to the
success of efforts to restore peace and stability to Congo (K)
and to the region.
</P>
<P>
''The strong U.N. delegation to this meeting is a concrete
manifestation of that concern and commitment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Defense Minister Pedro Sebastiao, Namibian Minister of
Home Affairs Jerry Ekandjo, Rwandan Col. Frank Mugambage, Ugandan
Minister of State for Defense Steven Kavuma, Zimbabwean Defense
Minister Moven e. Mahachi and others attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahachi said here Thursday that Rwandan and Angolan
forces must withdraw from Democratic Congo first before
zimbabwean and other allied forces would leave the country.
</P>
<P>
''Who came first must go first,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi hoped that the defense ministers meeting would draw up
the mechanism for a cease-fire agreed in principle at the second
Victoria Falls summit in Zimbabwe earlier this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
