<HEADLINE> Clinton Apologizes to Democratic Leaders in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton apologized over the Monica Lewinsky affair in private to
Senate Democratic leaders on Thursday. He also summoned his
Cabinet members to the White House for a similar session.
</P>
<P>
"He shared his feelings and apologized to us personally,"
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota told reporters
after the meeting in the White House residence.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said later his talk with the senators had been "a part
of this process I'm going through of talking to people... to ask
for their understanding, their forgiveness and their commitment
not to let the events of the moment in Washington deter us from
doing the people's work here." He spoke during a science awards
ceremony in the Roosevelt Room.
</P>
<P>
Daschle said the lawmakers accepted the president's apology but
also asked him whether there were new, damaging revelations yet to
surface.
</P>
<P>
"His answer was that, no, there were no surprises," Daschle
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton scheduled a late-afternoon meeting with members of his
Cabinet -- the first since January 23, when Clinton assured them
that reports he had a sexual affair with the former White House
intern were false.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Attorney General Janet Reno reaffirmed her
confidence in Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"There are so many factors that indicate that he has had the
ability to address issues in a comprehensive way that can truly
make a difference," she said at her weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
The Senate allies advised the president to keep up his campaign
of personal penance to save his presidency.
</P>
<P>
"We have expressed the hope that the president will continue to
demonstrate his contrition to his family, his friends and to the
American people," Daschle told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The senator added that he believed the president would survive
this political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Daschle appealed for fairness on Capitol Hill as the House of
Representatives prepares for possible impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
"The president's story needs to be heard and we need to get the
facts," Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
Daschle said Vice President Al Gore also attended the meeting,
which did not touch on the subject of a possible Clinton
resignation.
</P>
<P>
He said the senators "expressed the need to bring this to a
closure, to allow this country to heal, to allow us to work on the
nation's business."
</P>
<P>
Clinton returned to Washington D.C. early Thursday morning from
Florida, where he pleaded with Democratic party faithfuls for
forgiveness on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday before flying to Florida, Clinton met with House
Democratic leaders, who later described the president as
apologetic and determined to keep the country focused on issues he
deems most important, such as education and health care.
</P>
<P>
Even Democrats who have been among Clinton's biggest supporters
are expressing outrage at his handling of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
Several Republican members of Congress have called for
Clinton's resignation. Senator Sam Brownback of Kansas, asserted
Thursday that Clinton's ability to lead has been all but destroyed
and his actions have been "corrosive to our national character and
debased the office of the presidency." 
</P>
</TEXT>
