<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Bill Heads for Defeat Despite Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Legislation to overhaul
campaign finance rules suffered another blow in the U.S. Senate
Thursday despite support from a majority of senators.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted 52-48 to cut off debate and move to a final
decision on the bipartisan campaign finance measure authored by
Senators John McCain, a Republican, and Russ Feingold, a Democrat,
The vote was eight short of the 60 needed to overcome that
legislative hurdle.
</P>
<P>
Seven Republicans joined all 45 Democrats in voting to close
off debate. Supporters promised to try again before this session
of Congress ends, but the odds of overcoming the opposition led by
the Republican leadership appeared unlikely.
</P>
<P>
The Senate abandoned the McCain-Feingold bill last February
after failing to get those 60 votes by the same margin as on
Thursday's vote. The issue appeared dead for the year until last
month when House supporters of similar legislation, after months
of battling Republican leadership opposition, pushed their bill to
passage.
</P>
<P>
Feingold said his side had revived the issue after the House of
Representatives vote because "we owe it here in this body to the
American people to finish the job."
</P>
<P>
Both McCain-Feingold bill and the House bill, sponsored by
Representatives Christopher Shays, a Republican, and Marty Meehan,
a Democrat, would ban "soft money" -- unlimited and unregulated
donations to political parties. They also regulate issue ads that
purport to educate voters but are often used to influence
elections, and expand disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
Opponents argue that the bills are an unconstitutional assault
on free-speech rights and that the focus should be on
investigating campaign finance violations from the 1996 election
rather than making new laws.
</P>
<P>
Prevented from offering the measure independently, supporters
attached it as an amendment to an Interior Department spending
bill that must be approved before the new fiscal year begins
October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
