<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Countries Face Serious Food Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Southern
African Development Community (SADC) countries are facing serious
food problems with a forcast decline of about six percent in
maize harvest of 16.10 million tons this year against last year's
17.07 million tons.
</P>
<P>
A SADC official in charge of food security told reporters here
Thursday that current food problems are a result of erratic and
below normal rainfall in some of the southern countries as
against excessive rains and flooding in other parts of the region
such as Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Latest production estimates for the 1997/98 cereal harvest put
total production at 20.98 million tons against 22.38 million tons
in last season.
</P>
<P>
The decline was occasioned by the poor rainfall season in many
SADC countries including South Africa, Namibia, Lesotho, Zambia
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The SADC also faces an overall cereal deficit of 510,000 tons
for the 1998/1999 marketing year, he said, adding that the total
cereal availability of 25.71 million tons is insufficient to
cover total requirements estimated at 26.22 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The official cited large regional deficits in wheat and
sorghum as the cause of overall shortfall in the region.
</P>
<P>
As wheat is not easily substituted by other grains, the region
may have to import 1.35 million tons of wheat during the 1998/99
marketing year to cover the deficit.
</P>
<P>
Only maize is assessed as showing a regional surplus of 1.22
million tons, which according to him, is mostly due to high
carry-over stocks in South Africa. The surpluses are assessed for
South Africa, Mozambique, Swaziland and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports indicate that Namibia has issued
a 6-million-U.S. Dollar appeal for international assistance due to
poor harvests in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The food aid will cater for the emergency needs of 160,000
people in the north badly devastated by drought.
</P>
<P>
A crippling drought in southern Angola has prompted the
government to call for humanitarian assistance. Humanitarian
sources have indicated that more than 220,000 people in two of
Angola's provinces are at risk, having lost entire crops to the
El Nino-related drought.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the recent re-capture of government-held towns
in eastern Moxico Province by the opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola and increased hostilities in
the country may lead to increased movement of people seeking
refuge who will require food relief.
</P>
<P>
The grim food situation in the southern African region will be
reviewed by the 14 heads of state and government during their
summit scheduled for September 13 and 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
