<HEADLINE> UN Court Deputy Registrar Dies of Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The deputy registrar
of the United Nations court on Rwanda, Imelda Perry, died
Wednesday following a short illness, at the age of 51.
</P>
<P>
She died in the United States where she reportedly went for
medical treatment in early August, said Agwu Okali, registrar of
the Arusha-based International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda
(ICTR).
</P>
<P>
According to a news dispatch Thursday from Arusha in north
Tanzania, the registrar described Perry as a hardworking,
intelligent person, whose sudden death would cause a gap in the
tribunal's operations.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who joined the ICTR in March this year fit her position
so well that her absence "will be a big loss to the UN court,"
Okali told his staff Wednesday when announcing the death of
Perry.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR is the first international body charged specifically
with prosecuting crimes of genocide in Rwanda. The court was
created by the UN Security Council in November of 1994 after one
of the intense periods of mass exterminations in human history.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus,
were massacred by Hutu extremists in Rwanda in just three months
in the middle of that year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the UN court made landmark decisions by sentencing
Rwandan former Prime Minister Jean Kambanda life imprisonment for
six counts of genocide and crimes against humanity and finding
former Taba mayor Jean-Paul Akayesu guilty of genocide and crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
From 1989 to 1995, Perry worked as a trial attorney in a civil
litigation law firm appearing in state and federal courts in the
five boroughs of New York.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, she joined the United Nations Civilian Mission in
Haiti and worked extensively in the field prior to being
appointed as co-ordinator and legal officer of a regional office
and subsequently as desk officer and member of the four-person
co-ordination, analysis and reports unit of the mission.
</P>
<P>
Okali said that Perry will be given a befitting funeral in her
town of Saint Lucia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
