<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Ambassador to Head Radio Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A former U.S. ambassador
to Iraq and Yemen has been named director of Radio Free Iraq
the United States is setting up to encourage dissent in that
country, said its parent organization Thursday.
</P>
<P>
David Newton, ambassador in Baghdad from 1984 to 1988 and in
Sanaa from 1994 to 1997, will direct the Radio Free Iraq as part
of a U.S. government plan to encourage the Iraqi opposition to
overthrow President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The Radio Free Iraq will operate under the umbrella of Radio
Free Europe/Radio Liberty, the station set up during the Cold
War to broadcast to Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Radio Free Iraq wants to broadcast from the Czech capital of
Prague but Czech ministers and Prague residents are worried about
the security implications of basing the station there.
</P>
<P>
The radio station will start broadcasting in the autumn, said
Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty President Thomas Nine. 
</P>
