<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Ministerial Meeting Opens in Mauritius </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Council of
Ministers meeting of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) opened here Thursday in the northern resort of Grand Baie.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from 14 member countries are here to attend
the two-day meeting which will deliberate on a report proposed by
the senior officials meeting in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
The report mainly deals with progress in the implementation of
Council decisions since its last meeting in January this year in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Among the major issues to be discussed are sectoral progress
reports, update on protocol development and ratification,
recommendations on the Review and Rationalization of SADC Program
of Action as well as preparation for the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
Since the regional grouping was established in 1992, eight
protocols have been signed in diverse sectors such as water,
energy, trade, mining, education, transport and communications.
</P>
<P>
To date, four protocols have been ratified while RETOSA
(Regional Tourism Organization for Southern Africa) Charter has
already entered into force.
</P>
<P>
The RETOSA was set up to assist member states to formulate
tourism promotion policies and strategies.
</P>
<P>
Other protocols are expected to be ratified by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the opening of the meeting, South African
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo who is also chairman of the SADC
Council of Ministers urged members to speed up their pace in
ratifying the Trade Protocol, which seeks to lay the foundation
for a future economic union by establishing a SADC free-trade
area within eight years following the protocol's entry into
force.
</P>
<P>
"There are many more issues of pressing urgency that this
Council will have to deal with including the prevailing food
security situation in the region, promotion of trade and
investment in the current economic climate, facilitation of
movement of people in the Community as well as timely
implementation of the SADC Gender," he said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman also called on member states to focus on
production, trade and investment as well human resources
development in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
The SADC Council of Ministers which comprises ministers of
finance and economic planning meet at least twice a year. In
addition, special meetings are held to coordinate regional policy
in a particular field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
