<HEADLINE> European Union Tries to Help Resolve DRC Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has
expressed great concern about the on-going crisis in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and is working for resolving
the crisis through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We are very much worried about what is going on in the Congo,
and we are trying to support as much as we can all the
initiatives which are in the direction of cease-fire, peace, and
negotiations," the EU Special Envoy to the Great Lakes, Aldo
Ajello, said upon his arrival in Rwanda Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Ajello was at the second leg of his African tour, trying to
get the understanding of the Congolese issue, reported the Rwanda
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He had been in Addis-Ababa where he met the Organisation of
African Unity officials.
</P>
<P>
He said that he hoped to meet Rwandan government officials,
before his trip to Uganda to meet President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Ajello will also meet the embattled Congolese President,
Laurent Desire Kabila, before flying to New York to meet the
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The EU is ready to support an inter-African force to monitor
the cease-fire as suggested by the OAU, and which should not
include Congo's neighbors, Ajello said.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that EU would support financially that force,
that would work at creating conditions conducive to peace.
</P>
<P>
Ajello expressed great worries about the rising tides of
genocide and ethnic hate in the Great Lakes region which are
causing enormous suffering to the civilian populations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
