<HEADLINE> Iranian Army Deployed on Eastern Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran has deployed its army
along 700 kilometers of the country's eastern border in rising
tension between Tehran and the Afghan Taliban militia, a general
announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chief of the Joint Staff Command of the Armed Forces Ali
Shahbazi told reporters here that the army's troops were deployed
during the past month to follow the development beyond the border
and to strongly react to any aggression.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention how many troops have been sent to
the border with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The army's deployment came after the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) built up 70,000 troops on the northeastern
border with Afghanistan following a military maneuver early this
month in the northeastern province of Khorasan.
</P>
<P>
The chief of staff announced that the army will also launch a
grand maneuver in the near future along the eastern border in
Khorasan and the southeastern province of Sistan-Baluchestan.
</P>
<P>
Without giving the date of the maneuver, Shahbazi said that
the maneuver will be held with participation of ground forces,
armored, mechanized units with the support of the army's air
forces.
</P>
<P>
He said that new equipment will be tested in the maneuver and
modern bombers, advanced radar and communication system, a large
amount of tanks, and artillery will be used in the maneuver.
</P>
<P>
Shahbazi noted that the military exercises are aimed at
promoting the army's defensive capabilities against any possible
threat considering the insecurity and instability in the
neighboring Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The war games show that Iran will not tolerate any threat,
insecurity and drug smuggling in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the United States for expressing concern on
Iran's military buildup on the eastern border, saying that the
perseverance of peace and security in the region is against the
interests of the U.S. because it will not have pretext to keep its
forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
Rumors widely spread here said that Tehran has been prepared to
launch a military strike on the Taliban's targets as the Taliban
has confirmed the death of missing Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Iran earlier said that the Taliban forces kidnaped 11 Iranian
diplomats and a correspondent of the official news agency IRNA in
Mazari Sharif in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A Taliban spokesman announced on Thursday that the bodies of
nine Iranian diplomats have been found.
</P>
<P>
In a swift reaction, the Iranian Foreign Ministry stated that
Iran holds the Taliban and Pakistan responsible for the killing of
the Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
It also announced that Iran has the right to defend the
rights of Iranian nation against foreign aggression and the
Taliban and their supporters should bear the responsibility for
the consequences of Taliban's behavior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Monetary Policy Urged for SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A Mauritian senior
minister Thursday stressed on the importance of sound monetary, fiscal
and exchange rate policies to achieve macro-economic stability in the
southern African region.
</P>
<P>
A stable macro-economic framework is critical, over the long run,
for achieving the broad-based growth that is necessary to alleviate
poverty and combat underdevelopment, Rundheersing Bheenick, Mauritian
Minister of Economic Development and Regional Cooperation, told the
Council of Ministers meeting of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) at its opening session.
</P>
<P>
He said that the average growth rate in the sub-region is a
growing one which recorded at 4.4 percent in 1997, and 6.5
percent in 1996. The Gross Domestic Product of SADC was over 167
billion U.S. Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Significant progress has been noted in Angola, Botswana, Malawi and
Mozambique, which on average has grown by 6.5 percent in 1997. Other
members also registered quite satisfactory growth rates, he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment in the southern African region which has
a total population of 185 million is steadily increasing in Malawi,
Tanzania and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in 1996 was in single digit figure in Botswana,
Lesotho, Mauritius, Namibia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The task now is to spread the success more widely through
systematic pursuit of the development agenda, taking into
consideration specific country circumstances," he noted.
</P>
<P>
There is also an urgent need to reduce the costs of doing business
in southern Africa and to maximize productivity of resources, he said,
adding that market reforms have to be implemented to free up the
energies of the private sectors.
</P>
<P>
The SADC countries have signed protocols in key areas such as
trade, transport, energy, shared water courses and combating illicit
drugs since the organization was founded in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Protocol which lays foundation for a future economic
union by establishing a SADC free trade area in eight years
following its entry into force has so far been ratified by
Zimbabwe, Mauritius, Botswana and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
However, the protocol has to be ratified by two-thirds of the
members before its entry into force. Therefore, countries are urged
to speed up their process of ratifying it so that the regional economy
could benefit from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
