<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Fall Sharply with Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Growing concern over the
political situation in the United States hit Wall Street stocks
hard, which in turn sent European stock markets even deeper into
the red.
</P>
<P>
Shares on the London stock market were hit after an early slump
on Wall Street turned traders' screens into a sea of red.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of U.S. President Bill Clinton facing impeachment
proceedings sparked a similar tumble in London, which closed just
short of the days low. By the end of trading, the FTSE 100 Index
of leading shares was down 174.7 points at 5,136.6, wiping 30
billion pounds or 48 billion U.S. dollars off share prices.
</P>
<P>
This was also helped by the Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee's decision to keep interest rates unchanged at 7.5
percent. Manufacturers had been hoping for a fall.
</P>
<P>
Financial stocks led the market down with insurance companies
taking massive hits. But the prospect of more football teams being
taken over by media groups sent shares in several top clubs
rising.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, heavy opening losses on Wall Street and the
dollar's slump below the 1.70 Deutschmark level sparked another
slump in German stocks, too. The leading Dax index fell 293 points
to close at 4747, shedding 5.8 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the French stock market extended early losses to
trade at session lows, following another severe tumble on Wall
Street. The leading Cac-40 index closed down 172 points at 3589, a
drop of 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the banking sector had led the declines, as investors
fretted about the large provisions French banks set aside in the
first half to cover risk in Russia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's sharp pullback yesterday, although partly
anticipated, also weighed on sentiment, according to market
analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
