<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Warns to Use Force Over Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian President
Negasso Gidada Thursday warned that Ethiopia will use force
unless Eritrea unconditionally withdraws its troops from the
areas it forcibly occupied in May this year.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message, President Negasso said: "Defending
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the country will be
the major pre-occupation of the people and government of Ethiopia
in 1991 Ethiopian calendar.''
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Ethiopian calendar starts from September 11.
</P>
<P>
Negasso was quoted by the Ethiopia News Agency as saying,"The
use of force will come at the time when the government believes
is right and the chances for the peaceful settlement of the
crisis are fully exhausted."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Ministerial Committee of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) confirmed that Badme has always been part of
Ethiopia and the cause of the crisis is the invasion by Asmara.
</P>
<P>
"We are now awaiting the decision of the leaders of the OAU,"
the Ethiopian president said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to economic development in the country, Negasso said
encouraging achievements have been made in the economic, social
and political fields.
</P>
<P>
"Measures taken to ensure food self-sufficiency and food
security are bearing fruit and the extension program gathering
momentum," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural production in the coming new Ethiopian year is
expected to rise because of the prevailing suitable weather
condition, according to the president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in his new year message to the Ethiopian army,
Chief of Staff Tsadkan Gebre-Tensay said Thursday the Ethiopian
army will emerge victorious discharging the responsibility vested
in it to evict the Eritrean forces that violated the sovereignty
and territorial integrity of the country.
</P>
<P>
The army has drawn strategy which will enable it to decisively
crush the invading Eritrean force, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
