<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Clinton's Statements on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Friday welcomed
statements made by the United States President Bill Clinton that
his administration is working to help establish a bizonal and
bicommunal federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied when any U.N. Security Council member, and
especially a permanent member, remains firm on a bizonal,
bicommunal federation in Cyprus," government spokesman Christos
Stylianides told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the credentials of Cyprus' new ambassador to the
U.S. on Thursday, Clinton said that any solution to the Cyprus
issue should be "based on a bizonal, bicommunal federal framework
under U.N. auspices."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government "is trying to achieve a more forceful
stance from the international community and especially the five
permanent members of the (United Nations) Security Council, toward
the new Turkish effort to change the basis of the peace talks,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks came a few days after Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash proposed the establishment of a confederation of
"two equal and sovereign states" on the eastern Mediterranean
island. The Cypriot government has rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The world community has been trying to help reunify Cyprus
under the U.N. bi-zonal and by-communal formula. But no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
