<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Fall in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The producer prices
charged by factories and farms dropped 0.4 percent in August, due
largely to deflation in gasoline, automobiles and vegetables, the
Labor Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted decline in the Producer Price Index,
was the largest since January this year and exceeded analysts'
expectation for a slight 0.1 percent drop, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
For the first eight months of the year, producer prices have
fallen at a 1.4 percent annual rate, compared with a 1.2 percent
drop for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Much of the decline has come in energy costs, down 8.5 percent
in August and at a 14.8 percent annual rate so far this year. But
food costs also have fallen, 0.4 percent last month and at an 0.3
percent rate so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The department said "core" producer-price inflation, which
excludes the volatile food and energy components, has been
contained. Those prices edged 0.1 percent lower in August and, for
the first eight months of the year, have risen at just a 1.2
percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
August's price drop was propelled by an 8.5 percent decline in
gasoline, the largest for a single month since 1991. That brought
the price 30.1 percent lower than a year ago. The cost of
home-heating oil and residential electricity also fell, but
natural gas costs rose 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food prices fell 0.4 percent in August, with vegetable costs
plunging 20.6 percent. The cost of both tomatoes and onions was
cut nearly in half. Fruit, however, cost 1.7 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
Passenger car prices declined 1.7 percent in August with
General Motors production returning following a nearly two-month
strike. Computer prices continued to drop, 4.5 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
After a series of sharp increases, prescription drug costs fell
0.6 percent, but were still 21.3 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco increased 2.8 percent, and was 15.6 percent above a
year earlier, as companies continue their push to recover the cost
of multimillion-dollar liability lawsuits over smoking-related
deaths.
</P>
<P>
Children's clothing shot up 5.2 percent, rebounding from a 4.5
percent drop the month before. But women's and men's clothing
slipped 0.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Northern Ireland Prisoners Win Early Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Six Irish guerilla fighters
who won early release from jail walked out of Maize Prison near
Belfast on Friday under the province's peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Three of them are Roman Catholics who sought to end British
rule of Northern Ireland, while the other three are Protestants
who fought to prolong it, according to reports from Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners were freed under the peace deal signed in April
because of their allegiance to political parties who helped
negotiate it.
</P>
<P>
About 400 prisoners are expected to be released within two
years in Northern Ireland, about half of them by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
They were all convicted by so-called "diplock" courts, with
a single judge and no jury, which were set up under emergency
provisions imposed during the conflict, in which more than 3,600
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
A seventh man will be released soon. He is not aligned to any
armed group and was sentenced under special emergency provisions
imposed by Britain in Northern Ireland, and therefore qualified
for early release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
