<HEADLINE> Germany Poised for Record Rowing Medal Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Germany positioned
themselves for a record medal haul at the world rowing
championships in Cologne on Friday, qualifying three more boats
to get a total of 17 crews through to the weekend finals.
</P>
<P>
The United States will challenge the Germans with boats in 14
of the 24 finals, followed by Australia and Italy with 12 each
and Britain with 11.
</P>
<P>
Germany topped the medals table at last year's championships
in France with five golds.
</P>
<P>
Much of the attention on Saturday's finals will fall on
Britain's coxless four team who will be chasing its eighth world
championship gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Marnie McBean will also be looking to add to her
total of 10 world championship and Olympic medals by becoming the
first woman to reach the podium in six different events.
</P>
<P>
McBean, having already won world or Olympic medals in the
single sculls, double sculls, pairs, quadruple sculls and eights,
will secure her place in the rowing history books if she can
stroke Canada to a medal in the fours final on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
