<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidate Countries Per Capita GDP 40 Percent of EU Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The average real gross
domestic product (GDP) per person last year in countries applying
for European Union membership was 40 percent of the EU average.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita GDP in the candidate countries, however, saw an
increase of two percentage points since 1995, Eurostat, the
Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European Community said
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to its report, the candidate countries, excluding
Cyprus, averaged 7,500 current-price purchasing power standards
(PPS) for each person while EU member states averaged 19,000 PPS
per person.
</P>
<P>
PPS is an artificial currency used to remove the effect of
price differences between countries.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia had the highest per-capita PPS of 13,000 among the
candidate countries, while Greece -- with 13,100 PPS -- had the
lowest figure among the EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Candidate country Bulgaria had the lowest figure of 4,400 PPS,
while Luxembourg had the highest for the EU at 31,500 PPS.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10 candidate countries from central and eastern Europe,
Bulgaria and Romania posted decreases of real GDP in the past
year, while Poland, Slovakia, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Slovenia,
Lithuania, and the Czech Republic registered increases from one to
five percentage points during the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Urged to Prevent Epidemics After Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese authorities have
urged the nation to take emergency measures to prevent the spread
of epidemics after this summer's raging floods.
</P>
<P>
A notice issued by the General Offices of the Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee and the State Council states that the
floods have affected vast regions and more than 200 million
people, which increases the chances for epidemics in the flooded
areas.
</P>
<P>
The coming months will be critical for the country to provide
medical services to prevent diseases, the notice states, adding
that Party committees and governments at various levels must be
aware of the serious situation.
</P>
<P>
"Leading officials must adopt a responsibility system to ensure
that there are no serious diseases after the big disaster through
strict vigilance and by defending to the last," according to the
notice.
</P>
<P>
The notice urges strengthening the work of monitoring, analysis
and forecast, as well as alert to the plague and cholera. More
technicians should be sent to the flooded areas to disinfect areas
and kill mice, the notice states.
</P>
<P>
Water and food sanitation must be guaranteed, and rotten plants
and animal corpses must be properly disposed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there should be a publicity campaign in the media
to arouse people's attention, the notice states, adding that
publishing houses will print a large number of medical handbooks
for the flood victims and that disease-prevention courses will be
open in primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
It concludes that the governments should provide necessary
equipment and sufficient funding for the campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
