<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigation Starts into Passenger Jet's Emergency Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A team of experts arrived in
Shanghai today to start an investigation into an emergency landing
caused by a problem with the landing gear.
</P>
<P>
An MD-11 plane of China Eastern Airlines became aware of the
problem with the front landing gear shortly after it took off from
Hongqiao Airport in Shanghai for Beijing at 7:38 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot was granted approval by the airport control center to
return to Hongqiao Airport. After two trials, the plane could not
put down its landing gear and circled the airport for more than
three hours. The plane then made an emergency landing after most
of its fuel had been used up.
</P>
<P>
Experts' preliminary conclusions are that the accident was
triggered by a broken bolt in the control barrel of the front
chassis.
</P>
<P>
The group is being led by Wang Li'an, deputy director of the
Civil Aviation Administration of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
