<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Records Deteriorating Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The air quality in urban
China has deteriorated somewhat over the past week, according to
the China Environmental Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
The center's latest air quality report indicated less
precipitation, dry air and increased levels of suspended particles
in Lanzhou, Hohhot and Taiyuan in northern China, with rising
sulphur dioxide levels reported in southwestern China's Chongqing
Municipality. The four cities reported moderate air pollution
between September 4-10.
</P>
<P>
Experts note the weather conditions associated with the
approach of autumn are unfavorable for dispersing pollutants and
will most likely lead to a further deterioration in the urban air
quality.
</P>
<P>
A number of cities, including Beijing, Tianjin, Xi'an and
Guangzhou, recorded slight air pollution over the past week,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The major problem in Guangzhou centered on levels of nitrogen
oxide, while other cities reported high levels of suspended
particles.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four cities, including Shanghai, Nanjing, Wuhan and
Kunming, reported good air quality.
</P>
<P>
Nine cities -- Nanning, Shantou, Wenzhou, Ningbo, Xiamen,
Zhanjiang, Shenzhen, Haikou and Beihai -- enjoyed excellent air
quality during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
