<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The State Development
Bank of China will loan 13 billion yuan (1.57 billion
U.S. dollars) to Shanghai over the next three-to-five years for
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's mayor, Xu Kuangdi, and bank president Chen Yuan
signed a letter of intent here today.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used for eight major projects, including
cleaning the fouled Suzhou River, setting up trash burning plant
and building and expanding highways.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the investment is an experiment of the State
Development Bank in cooperation with local governments.
</P>
<P>
The bank has already provided 7.5 billion yuan of loans to
Shanghai since 1994 in building power stations, ports and
airports. It also plans other joint projects in financial
services.  
