<HEADLINE> Campaign Starts in South Asia Against Gender-based </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A curtain raiser was
launched here Friday for a campaign in the South Asian region to
eradicate gender-based violence.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, a dramatic play was presented to shed light on
gender-based violence including physical aggression, sexual abuse,
emotional abuse and political violence.
</P>
<P>
The curtain raiser was launched on the sidelines of a meeting
on gender mainstreaming in the South Asian region, which is
jointly organized by the Nepali government and the U.N.
Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM).
</P>
<P>
As part of the observance of the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, UNIFEM initiated early this
year in the Latin America and Caribbean region a global campaign,
the first of its kind, to eradicate gender-based violence.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, the campaign was launched in late July in Nigeria
while in the Asia-Pacific region, the campaign started on August
30 in the Philippines under the slogan of "A Life Free of
Violence: It's Our Right."
</P>
<P>
UNIFEM said that its South Asian Regional Office based in New
Delhi will be observing this campaign in the region through 16
days of activism from November 25 to December 10 this year,
involving different forms of media, women organizations, college
students and youth, governments and U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
It said that the campaign is taking different forms in
different countries and includes rallies, marches, cultural
programs, essay competitions and publication of various materials
on violence against women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
