<HEADLINE> Rain Washes out First Day Contest at FAI World Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Heavy Rain washed out the
first day competitions of the China Cup aerobatics world grand
prix here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"As scheduled, there should be competitions today," said Jean
Louis Monnet, chief executive of the Federation Aeronautique
Internationale (FAI) world grand prix. "But as also scheduled, it
should be a fine today. The weather, however, is too bad, so we
have to call off the competitions."
</P>
<P>
An exhibition show by renowned British aerobatics team Golden
Dreams was put on in its stead, which was later hailed by FAI
president Eilif Ness as the "greatest festival of aerobatics ever
held".
</P>
<P>
Some 5000 spectators braved nasty rain to come and see the
dazzling performances by world's best pilots from the Malaysia-ba
sed Golden Dreams team.
</P>
<P>
The pilots took off in turn, with their roaring Planes zooming
up almost vertically into the sky. They made superb rolling
turns, spins, hammerheads, tail slides and loops, leaving
spectators watching agape, apparently too startled to applaud.
</P>
<P>
"I can hardly imagine how they could manage this," said the
tournament's director Liu Liancheng, "They can pilot their planes
like leaves in the choppy wind. You will not believe it until you
see it."
</P>
<P>
The Grand Prix attracted all the 24 top finishers of last
year's world championships, who will tour eight Chinese cities of
Shanghai, Nanjing, Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou, Wuhan and
Changsha.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Prix will end on November 2nd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
