<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Temperatures Hit New High for August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- August was the eighth
month in a row to set a new average high temperature worldwide,
according to a report by U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The average global temperature for August was 61.4 degrees
Fahrenheit, the report said. This broke the previous record of
61.1 degrees set in 1997 and is 1.3 degrees above the long-term
average of 60.1 degrees for this month.
</P>
<P>
NOAA said during August, warm temperature prevailed over most
areas of the globe, with cool areas only in Europe, Alaska,
Siberia, Bangladesh, the South Atlantic and the Central Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Owing to La Nina, the sea surface temperatures in the Central
Pacific were below normal.
</P>
<P>
As for the United States, the temperature for the same period
was 56.2 degrees, lower than the same period in 1934 with a
record 56.9 degrees for January to August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
