<HEADLINE> Philippine President Vows to Crack Down on Muslim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada vowed Friday to crack down hard on the country's Muslim
extremist group Abu Sayyaf should they refuse to surrender or
release unharmed their captives.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also ruled out any amnesty for Abdujarak Abubakar
Janjalani, head of the group, saying he has to face trial and
punishment first before such privilege can even be considered.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Estrada said Abu Sayyaf
members, who have been blamed for a string of abductions in
southern Mindanao, should stop their lawless operations or face
the full might of the government forces.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said Abu Sayyaf members should realize by now that he
is more determined than ever to restore peace and order not only
in Metro Manila but nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the government forces are closing in on the Abu
Sayyaf and he is expecting a breakthrough in the abduction cases
Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf members abducted five people, including a foreign
businessman in southern Zamboanga del Sur province Wednesday, one
day after kidnapping an Italian priest and 12 of his parishioners
in Zamboanga del Norte province.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf, with which the government has refused to open peace
talks, is one of the country's two Muslim groups still fighting
the government. The other is the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) which already began peace talks with the government in
January 1997. 
