<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Flight Ban on Yugoslav Carriers Should Be Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- European Commission
President Jacques Santer demanded on Friday that the flight ban on
Yugoslav carriers be observed by all European Union (EU) member
states.
</P>
<P>
"The decision taken by the 15 (EU member states) has to be
implemented by all 15 countries," Santer said in a written
statement.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the executive body of the 15-nation European Union
added that the sanction against Yugoslavia would become
meaningless if one or several member states did not "play the
game" as previously agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
EU member state Britain claimed, citing procedural reasons,
that it could not implement the flight ban that was agreed upon
unanimously by the European council of foreign ministers in late
June and finalized by the same council last weekend.
</P>
<P>
It said that under a 1959 agreement with Yugoslavia, it is
required to give 12 months notice before canceling flights from
that country.
</P>
<P>
The British authorities quoted the European community treaty as
stipulating that member states would have to honor international
agreements and contracts with non-EU countries as well.
</P>
<P>
Greece also faces the same issue. Spain, that had held a
similar argument, later decided to implement the flight ban.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav national carrier JAT stopped flying to Germany,
Sweden, Austria, the Netherlands and Denmark after these EU member
states suspended landing rights following enforcement of the
flight ban on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Santer said the next commission meeting, scheduled for
Wednesday, will examine the implementation of the flight ban by
member states. 
</P>
