<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwegian Jenssen Ties World Record at Pentathlon Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Norway's Bjorn Jenssen
turned up a world record-tying performance in the shooting here
today to take the lead in men's individual event on the first day
of the CISM 46th Military Pentathlon World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Sweden and the Netherlands were the squads to shine in the
men's and women's team event, standing atop the table after the
first day's shooting events.
</P>
<P>
Jenssen tied the world record of 200 hits to collect a maximum
1140 points in the precision and rapid shootings event, the first
discipline in the seven-day pentathlon worlds.
</P>
<P>
Anton Bondesson of Sweden followed up with 1133 points from
199 hits, with Dutchman H. Stienissen the third 1126 from 198.
</P>
<P>
"It's fantastic," Jenssen said. "If everything is OK, you need
a little good luck (to make 200 hits). I know I can shoot 200
(hits), ... but I didn't make it in competition."
</P>
<P>
"My aim is to finish 5,000 (points overall), but it's not easy
for me," Jenssen added.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Carlos Silva of Brazil had a poor day, just
managing an indifferent 187 hits.
</P>
<P>
"He's nervous, and put too much pressure on himself. He
should make 195 (hits) or more," Brazil's coach Carlos Felipe
said. "Anyway, he's not a good shooter."
</P>
<P>
In the women's individual event, China's Wang Lianying,
four-time champion in a row, shared the first place with three
other athletes on 193 points.
</P>
<P>
In the team divisions, Sweden's male athletes provisionally
occupied the top position with 4,462 points, Norway coming on
second with 4,448 and defending champion China third on 4,399.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch women's shooters accumulated 3,224 points to finish
first before Denmark on 3,203 and Sweden on 3,182. The title
holders China were fourth on 3,161 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
