<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Financial Practitioners Promote Ethics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 representatives
from Hong Kong's financial industry participated in a conference
here Friday on the promotion of professional ethics in the
securities, futures and investments sectors.
</P>
<P>
The high-profile conference was jointly organized by nine local
institutions including the Stock Exchange, Futures Exchange,
Securities Institute and Hong Kong Clearing, and supported by the
Securities and Futures Commission and the Independent Commission
Against Corruption.
</P>
<P>
Alec Tsui, chief executive of the Stock Exchange and chairman
of the organizing committee, delivered the opening remarks. He
said the continued efforts Hong Kong has made in maintaining and
enhancing business ethics have played a significant role in
securing its position as a major international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was a clear declaration to the international
community that Hong Kong financial industry places great value on
professional ethics, said Tsui.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang shared his views with the
industry's practitioners. "Ethics represented the correct way of
human behavior in dealing with others and it is a vital element in
 the conduct of business, whether in the public or private
sectors," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is a professional market and we have reason to
demand a higher (ethical) standard of our practitioners in respect
of their advice to their clients," Tsang noted.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the view that ethics supplement rules and
regulations. "Rules and regulations, no matter how tight, will not
deliver a clean market without an ethical mind. A set of rules
will never be able to cover the entire spectrum of activities in
any financial market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference constituted part of a Professional Ethics
Program, which, initiated by local financial institutions, will
last two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
