<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Consumption to Boost Swedish Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish economy will
continue to grow this and next year despite the Asian crisis and
the financial turmoils on world markets, according to a forecast
by HUI, the Swedish Retailers and Wholesaler Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
After several years of belt-tightening, consumers are expected
to start shopping with enthusiasm, said the Institute. Private
consumption is expected to take the place of exports as the motor
driving Swedish industry.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending is expected to increase by 3.2 percent this
year and by 3 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Retailers had a very strong month in August. The Swedish
furniture company IKEA, for example, reported a 35 percent growth
of sales, on the same month in 1997. Clothing and shoe sales
climbed by 42.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, HUI feels that the financial turmoils are only
transitory.
</P>
<P>
However, the Institute predicted that the Swedish joblessness
will be 6.7 percent this year, dipping to 6 percent in 1999. This
indicates that the government's goal of less than 4 percent
unemployment by the year 2000 would not be realized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
