<HEADLINE> Lubutu Town Retaken From Congolese Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- President Laurent Kabila's
troops have retaken the eastern town of Lubutu in the Democratic
Republic of Congo after intense bombardments, a report reaching
here from Kinshasa said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lubutu, located on the highway between the third city of
Kisangani and eastern town of Bukavu bordering Rwanda, returned
to the embraces of Kabila's loyalists with 45 rebels killed and
19 taken prisoner, a communique from the Information Ministry was
quoted by state television as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the news did not say when Kabila's loyalists took the
town.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who took up arms on August 2 to oust Kabila,
refused to abide by a cease-fire and claimed they had won fresh
victories in other eastern front areas of Congo, have not been
invited to go to Ethiopia for regional talks on the settlement of
the Congo conflict which resumed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
No sign of a breakthrough on a cease-fire is imminent when
defense ministers of seven neighboring countries are meeting in
Addis Ababa to continue their negotiations on the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia sent troops to intervene on
August 20 and thus turned the tide of fighting in western Congo,
but the rebels are still occupying large areas in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
President Kabila refuses to recognize the rebel group of the
Congolese Democratic Coalition as an internal movement and his
allied backers insist on talking with its alleged sponsors of
Rwanda and Uganda for a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
This hinders the achievement of a breakthrough on a cease-fire
in the war-torn Congo (K). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
