<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Become Innovation &AMP; Tech Center: Advisor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong needs urgently to
develop itself into a center of innovation and technology to face
the challenges in the knowledge-based, global economy of the 21st
century, an advisor of the HK chief executive on technology said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chang-Lin Tien, chairman of the Chief Executive's
Commission on Innovation and Technology established in March 1998,
suggested "a new vision" which he said Hong Kong should take in
order to maintain its international competitiveness. And the new
vision is "Hong Kong as a center of innovation and technology."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong needs to broaden its economic base to cushion itself
from external shocks like the Asian financial turmoil," the
engineering professor of University of California, Berkeley, said
in an address at a luncheon sponsored by the American Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to Professor Tien, in the late 1970s, 24 percent of
Hong Kong's economy was based on manufacturing while today only 7
percent was built on manufacturing because of a massive shift of
industrial facilities to the Pearl River Delta in southern China
over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
He said: "There is certainly a silver lining" in the Asian
financial turmoil, which, though painful, has forced more and more
Hong Kong people to come to realize the need to develop hi-tech
and knowledge-based industry.
</P>
<P>
"This is really an urgent business right now," he said, adding
"Time is essential."
</P>
<P>
Professor Tien suggested that Hong Kong invest in higher skills
and more advanced technologies to increase productivity, promote
innovation and engage in higher value-added activities.
</P>
<P>
That is part of the content of an interim report Tien and his
commission are now preparing to advise the Special Administrative
Region (SAR) government on policies related to technology and
industry.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, when delivering his policy
address on October 7, may take in some recommendations from the
report to be submitted by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Professor Tien said his commission's mission is to identify the
measures needed to realize Hong Kong's new vision. "I am
optimistic," said the chairman, who listed a string of Hong Kong's
strengths -- free market policies, a sound legal system, access
to mainland market, technology and expertise, a productive and
adaptable workforce, entrepreneurial culture and a vibrant and
well-developed capital market.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out Hong Kong's weaknesses, such as meager
input in research and development and lack of research centers, a
technology culture and resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0126 </DOCNO>
