<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African, Namibian Bourses Sign Coop Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Johannesburg Stock
Exchange (JSE) of South Africa and the Namibian Stock Exchange
(NSE) Friday signed in Windhoek a cooperation agreement over
exchanges of technology, skills and information.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which falls within the framework of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) harmonization program,
includes the transfer of expertise and information on training,
marketing and research.
</P>
<P>
JSE spokeswoman Suzette Plantema said at a news briefing that
the first result of the pact would be the replacement of the
trading systems of the NSE and its eventual full automation.
</P>
<P>
"The stock exchanges of the SADC sub-region have formed a
committee which meets to identify areas of cooperation and
harmonization in the interests of the development of the Southern
African capital markets.
</P>
<P>
"The memorandum of understanding between the JSE and the NSE
is a first step in taking these relationships into more formal
links and is open to other SADC exchanges to join in the future,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The JSE and the NSE were already working on facilities for the
latter to use the former's world-class Johannesburg equities
trade computer system. Live prices of securities on both
exchanges would be widely disseminated across the region and
internationally from November this year.
</P>
<P>
By the same date, NSE member brokers would also have the JSE
broker deal accounting system, which offers improved client
administration, security and regulation.
</P>
<P>
The next phase of the agreement to be effected next year
includes NSE access to the computerized clearing and settlement
systems being implemented in the local market under the JSE's
share transactions totally electronic project.
</P>
<P>
This would make the Namibian and South African market comply
with the highest international standards of capital market
security, efficiency and investor protection, meaning that paper
certificates would no longer be used in the settlement of stock
exchange trades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
