<HEADLINE> Pakistan, IMF Mission Begin Technical Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A 3-member team of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) which arrived here Friday began
"technical discussion" with the Pakistani government officials on
the country's macro-economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission, who will stay here for two weeks, will review
macro-economic targets including budget deficit, inflation,
imports, trade, balance of payments position and performance of
the agricultural and industrial sectors during the first week of
its stay, according to sources in the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
IMF Middle East Division Head Antonio Furtado will join the
mission on September 16 for holding policy level talks on the
reactivation of a loan facility of 1.6 billion U.S. dollars put on
hold following Pakistan's nuclear tests in May and new financial
package for the country in the changed economic scenario, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Advisor to the Prime Minister on Finance and Economic Affairs
Hafiz Pasha will head the Pakistani side during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission will collect the data and other information
about the macro-economic variables to measure the performance of
the country's economy particularly after the economic sanctions
imposed on it by the West in the wake of its nuclear tests, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the talks between IMF and Pakistan will be to
determine the quantum of financing to bridge the gap in the
country's external finances, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
