<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedishi Charity Group Aids Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A private charity
organization in Sweden is devoting itself to raising money for the
people hit by the catastrophic floods in China this summer.
</P>
<P>
Star of Hope International, a Stockholm-based development and
relief aid organization, is providing 600,000 Swedish crowns
(about 100,000 U.S. dollars) worth of medicine and hardtack to
people in three counties in Hubei, Jiangxi and Heilongjiang
provinces, which have been most affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Bjorg Farstad, a senior official with the organization,
said: "This vitamin and mineral biscuit gives a person all the
vitamins, minerals and protein that human needs for a day. It's a
good supplement to the rice the people receive from the
government."
</P>
<P>
Farstad is also authorized by her group to buy quality medicine
at local pharmaceutical companies with the special fund of 600,000
crowns.
</P>
<P>
"Because the problem is too big for China considering the
magnitude of the disaster, I hope that other governments and
other organizations will do something," she said.
</P>
<P>
Star of Hope International is campaigning in the media to
solicit more aid in Sweden for the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
"We have even contacted all Chinese restaurants in my country
to see what they can do," said Farstad, citing that her colleagues
in Stockholm are working hard to raise fund.
</P>
<P>
Livia Alm, a nutrition expert with the Karolinska Institute of
the Medical University of Sweden, said: "I think the Chinese
government has done an excellent job. It has done everything it
could."
</P>
<P>
"The victims' temporary settlements are very well organized
and the people are well taken of," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see anyone actually suffering from urgent matters,
they are given food, medical care and schooling," said Alm, also a
professor of Biotechnology Department at Shanghai Fisheries
University.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old Alm said she endeavored to raise funds to buy
the special biscuit, which has been developed specifically for
flood and earthquake disaster victims.
</P>
<P>
"The biscuit can be used for anyone from a six-month-old child
on up, and the medicine helps fight against intestinal infection,
skin infections and other diseases," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see that these people are not left alone. The
Chinese people are kind to each other, and the victims are
provided with food, clinics and schools," Alm added.
</P>
<P>
Farstad said: "I don't know how much we will be able to assist
these flood victims after this first donation, but I hope that we
can do more."
</P>
<P>
The organization works mainly to help women and children. It
promotes education for poor children from infancy to youth when
they can get jobs and take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
"In the near future, Star of Hope International will help the
orphans in the country through China Charity Federation," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, the organization is primarily focusing on the
flood-hit areas in China.
</P>
<P>
The flood disaster in the northeastern, central and eastern
provinces killed 3,004 people, cost 166.6 billion yuan in economic
loss, affected more than 200 million residents and has left about
20 million homeless.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
