<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Meeting on Gender Mainstreaming Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The two-day meeting on
gender mainstreaming in the South Asian region began here Friday
with focus on evolving a strategy and time frame for a regional
intervention for engendering the planning process.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are secretaries and senior officials of
the women affairs ministries, members of national planning
commissions, representatives of key NGOs and activists from the
seven member countries of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of U.N. agencies are also present at the
meeting, organized jointly by the Nepali government and the U.N.
Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Chandni Joshi, regional program advisor
of UNIFEM, noted that at the Fourth World Conference on Women in
Beijing in September 1995, it was unanimously agreed and
emphasized time and again that gender mainstreaming was one of the
fundamental strategies to achieve equality between women and men.
</P>
<P>
But the second South Asian regional meeting on women issues
which ended here Thursday noted that there is a lack of proper
mainstreaming of gender consideration across sectors in the
region, where gender continues to be seen as a "women's issue" and
the responsibility of the women affairs ministries only.
</P>
<P>
According to UNIFEM, gender mainstreaming refers to a strategy
for making gender considerations an integral dimension in the
design, implementation, monitoring and evaluation of policies and
programs in all political, economic and societal spheres so that
inequality is not perpetuated and women and men can benefit
equally.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, participants are scheduled to share their
experiences and contribute expertise toward developing new ideas
and plans of action for gender mainstreaming in this region.
</P>
<P>
They will also review the progress that has been made and
identify challenges facing SAARC countries in this regard.
</P>
<P>
At the working session of the meeting Friday, representatives
of India, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh and the Maldives presented
case study and perspectives respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
