<HEADLINE> Asia Draw for Qualifying Rounds for Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Football
Confederation Friday carried out its draw for the Olympic
qualifying tournament for Sydney 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
A total of 34 teams entered for the Asian qualifying rounds.
Only three places are available for Asia in the Sydney Olympics
Games.
</P>
<P>
In the draw supervised by the AFC Secretary-General Peter
Velappan, the 34 teams were divided into nine groups based on
performance, logistic and economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
In the preliminary matches to be held between February 1, 1999
to June 30, 1999, teams must play home and away matches with each
other in the group, according to a press release by the AFC here.
</P>
<P>
Each group champion will then move into the final qualifying
round where the nine group winners will then be divided into
three group of three teams each.
</P>
<P>
The Asian final qualifying round matches will be held from
September 1, 1999 to November 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Only the three group champions in the Asian final round will
qualify for the Sydney Olympics scheduled from September 13 to
30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the last Olympics in Atlanta, the United States in 1996,
the three Asian representatives were Japan, Saudi Arabia, South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
China has a tough group which features Vietnam, Myanmar and
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Following are teams in groups for Asian Qualifying Rounds for
the Sydney 2000 Olympics:
</P>
<P>
Group 1: United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Yemen
</P>
<P>
Group 2: Kuwait, Oman, Syria
</P>
<P>
Group 3: Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Jordan
</P>
<P>
Group 4: Iran, Lebanon, Bahrain
</P>
<P>
Group 5: Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan,
Turkmenistan,Uzbekistan
</P>
<P>
Group 6: Japan, MALAYSIA, Hong Kong of China, Nepal
</P>
<P>
Group 7: China, Vietnam, Myanmar, DPR Korea
</P>
<P>
Group 8: South Korea, Indonesia, Sri Lanka, Chinese Taipei
</P>
<P>
Group 9: Thailand, Singapore, India, Laos, Brunei.
</P>
