<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Softens Stand on CTBT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee said Friday that India accepted the spirit underlying the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), which he had described
earlier as discriminative.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
would take a decision on whether to sign the CTBT after
discussions with key interlocutors, Vajpayee said in Lucknow,
capital city of north Uttar Pradesh, at the end of his two-day
visit to the state.
</P>
<P>
Following India's nuclear tests last May, the Indian government
declared a moratorium on further tests while refusing to sign the
CTBT on the ground that it was discriminative to countries like
India.
</P>
<P>
But under pressure both at home and abroad on the nuclear
issue, the government had privately told certain foreign
governments that it was not averse to signing the treaty.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India, the Indian prime
minister asserted that something more is required to be done by
the nuclear weapon states before his country thinks of signing the
CTBT but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India daily reported Wednesday that India was
inching closer to signing the CTBT but fears of an adverse
political fallout were preventing the Vajpayee government from
putting its signature to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that adhering to the CTBT will not jeopardize our
security concerns," the paper quoted a senior official in the
prime minister's office as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ruling BJP is now planning to talk to all political parties
in the next couple of weeks to get their views and prepare the
ground for eventually signing of the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
However, the BJP leaders are worried that the Congress and
other opposition parties could take this opportunity to try to
pull down the Vajpayee government.
</P>
<P>
There is fear among the Indian leaders that without getting
something in return from the United States and other nuclear
powers, it will be difficult to sell the treaty to the Indian
people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
