<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Helps Rescue Water System in Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC) Friday flew 40 tons of vital water
treatment chemicals from Nairobi to help rescue water system in
violent Democratic Congo's capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"The emergency in Kinshasa today is clean water. The city's
general hygiene and millions of citizens depend on this. Without
this chlorine, the city's water treatment will come to a
standstill today," said the ICRC in a statement issued here.
</P>
<P>
The water supply in Kinshasa relies on three main water
treatment plants that need four types of chemicals, including
chlorine, in order to provide 250 million liters of potable water
per day for its citizens. Without any one chemical, the whole
system falls apart, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Pierre-Yves Monnard, an ICRC official in Kinshasa, was quoted
as saying that without clean water, epidemics might spread in the
city with over five million inhabitants who would have to resort
to drinking water from contaminated wells or the two rivers that
run through the city.
</P>
<P>
"Both the Congo and Ndjili rivers are extremely muddy,
containing high amounts of lethal pathogens and therefore not fit
for human consumption," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC official said that citizens of Kinshasa have few
resources to boil contaminated water to ensure proper hygiene as
there is a lack of firewood in the city and coal is extremely
expensive.
</P>
<P>
International donors have also lined up to join in an airlift
of food and medical supplies for Kinshasa, which was cut off from
port supplies because of the civil war since August 2.
</P>
<P>
The road and rail corridor through which 75 percent of food
and supplies enter Kinshasa from Matadi remains closed because of
the fighting between the Tutsi-led rebels and the government
troops loyal to Congolese President Laurent Kabila since last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
