<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Uncovers Cellular Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian police has tracked
down a cellular phone cloning syndicate, leading to the arrest of
five suspects, a report by the Post Express newspaper said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tauye Shobajo, an officer of Task Force on Telecommunications
and Postal Offenses said the team started investigations upon
report by a furniture company executive in Lagos who complained
of persistent outrageous cellular bills.
</P>
<P>
Surveillance on the cloned line led to the arrest of an
Olufemi Okunyelu, an employee of the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation in Kaduna, who was using the cloned set.
</P>
<P>
Based on the suspect's confession, the police arrested
Akinkunmi Ashipa, an agent who provided the set, and eventually
tracked down the three other suspects.
</P>
<P>
Items found in the possession of these suspects include
different types of cellular handsets, accessories, computer sets
and a scanner, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Further investigations have discovered more victims, among
who is a retired general, the officer added. 
</P>
