<HEADLINE> Turkey Condemns Killing of Iranian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Friday strongly
condemned the killing of nine Iranian diplomats based in northern
Afghanistan by the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry said that "we heard
the news that the kidnaped Iranian diplomats were killed in
Afghanistan with great anxiety and indignation."
</P>
<P>
Turkey called on the international community to take effective
measures in a bid to prevent such kinds of inhuman actions in the
future, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Iran said it held the Afghan Taliban militia and
their supporter Pakistan responsible for the killing of the
Iranian diplomats, who were missing after the Taliban captured the
northern Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Iran claimed that altogether 11 diplomats and a correspondent
of its official news agency were kidnaped by the Taliban, who
denied knowing anything about the whereabouts of those people.
</P>
<P>
Not until Thursday did the Taliban confirmed nine of the
diplomats have been killed by "renegade forces" and their bodies
found, but it did not mention the fate of the others.
</P>
<P>
Iran has vowed to take revenge on the Taliban. Over the past
few days, it massed about 70,000 troops along the border with
Afghanistan, making a revenge attack or even a military incursion
possible.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been in contact with Afghan opposition leaders
including ousted President Burhanuddin Rabbani and urged for a
broad based government in the country. It feared the Taliban's
control of the country would encourage fundamentalist trend in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Confident Duma Will Confirm Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin Friday said he has no doubt that Yevgeny Primakov will be
confirmed as prime minister in the State Duma, lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The president said his confidence was based on popular support
for the nominee.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin nominated Primakov for premier on Thursday after the
Duma rejected Viktor Chernomyrdin twice for the prime minister's
post. The lawmakers will vote on Yeltsin's third nomination at
17:00 local time Friday.
</P>
<P>
Russia will survive a crucial political crisis due to the
politicians' compromise at the critical moment, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government is facing very difficult tasks. It is
necessary to urgently lower prices, fill the shops with goods
again, restore the banking system, and guarantee the safety of
bank deposits, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed those issues can be solved by the new
government with the support of both the president and the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The president also called on all branches of government to make
joint efforts to overcome the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday Yeltsin and Primakov had a meeting in the
Kremlin. Both were reported to agree that the priority at present
is to iron out the economic crisis and pave the way for economic
growth. 
</P>
