<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Persist in 'Strike Hard' Drive, State Councillor Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Luo Gan, China's top law
enforcement official and state councillor, said today that the
country must persist in its "strike hard" anti-crime drive to
reduce the rising rate of serious criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
"Generally speaking, the public security situation in the first
half of this year has been stable, but crime rates in some places
are rising sharply and the increase of certain categories of
felonies has been prominent," Luo said.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a plenary meeting of the Central Committee
of Comprehensive Management of Public Security under the Chinese
Communist Party, of which he is director.
</P>
<P>
He is also a Political Bureau member of the CPC Central
Committee and head of the Central Political and Legal Committee of
the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Localities must step up efforts to crack down on alarming
crimes in their areas and beat arrogant and aggressive criminals
to curb the rising crime rate and maintain a sound and safe social
order, Luo said at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement bodies should especially focus their attention
on the ongoing fight against smugglers in accordance with the
order given by President Jiang Zemin on the anti-smuggling fight.
</P>
<P>
To root out potential factors causing social instability, more
work has to be done to build "safe and civilized" communities
where neighborhoods have to be mobilized to help police
communities, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he called on law enforcement officers in flood-hit
areas to work hard to provide a favorable environment for flooding
victims to rebuild their homes and regain prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also heard work reports on helping released
prisoners find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Luo said that this work is important for preventing and
reducing recidivism and needs support from the whole society.
</P>
<P>
Vice-chairman of the top legislature Cao Zhi, top judge Xiao
Yang and top prosecutor Han Zhubin also attended the meeting
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
