<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unilateral Inspections of Fishing Ban Show Increased Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Recent unilateral inspections
of the Yellow and East China seas revealed effective compliance with
the summer fishing ban, according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"China has expanded its moratorium in terms of both time and
scope, and the number of fishing boats violating the ban has
continued to decline," according to Peng Xiaohua, an official with
the ministry's Fisheries Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the check was to ensure compliance with the
offshore fishing moratorium, said Peng, adding that the check
indicated the nation's strong commitment to promoting the
sustainable development of fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The moratorium applies to over 90,000 Chinese fishing boats,
including over 22,000 operating in the East China Sea. The check
revealed that only two per thousand boats in the East China Sea
violated the fishing ban this year, compared with 3.5 per
thousand during last summer's moratorium.
</P>
<P>
Peng attributed the improvement to an increasing awareness of
the need for the ban and efforts local governments have made to
strengthen both management and supervision.
</P>
<P>
All local fisheries departments operating in the East China Sea
area have adopted stern measures towards illegal boats, including
fines and the confiscation of nets, according to Zhang Qiuhua,
assistant director of the Bureau of the East China Sea Fisheries
Management and Fishing Port Superintendency.
</P>
<P>
Peng admitted that falling output in the first half of the year
and the extension of moratorium period have prompted some
fishermen to ignore the ban.
</P>
<P>
Fishing with trawl nets and other "hazardous fishing equipment"
has been banned for a three month period over an area ranging from
26 degrees to 35 degrees north latitude, and for two months in
areas north of 35 degrees and from 24.5 degrees to 26 degrees
north latitude.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the overall summer fishing ban in 1995. The
two month ban in effect over the past three years has helped
protect the natural habitat for fry. The ban has helped increase
the size of major fish species, such as hairtail, and has at the
same time improved offshore output figures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1997 show that the output for hairtail grew by
15 percent and for small yellow croaker by 38 percent compared
to figure for 1994 before introduction of the moratorium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
