<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Pursue Charter Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
create in January 1999 a preparatory constitutional commission to
study proposed changes to the country's 1987 Constitution, the
Presidential Press Office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a press release that the commission will be
composed of respected jurists, political scientists, and
representatives of the Church and other sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada was quoted as telling a forum Thursday
night that whatever amendments to the charter are approved will
take effect after his term.
</P>
<P>
According to Estrada, after the commission finished its study,
the election of delegates to the Constitutional Convention will be
held to coincide with the mid-term election in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the selection of the commission's membership has
begun, but the commission itself will be convened in next January.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a commission on constitutional reforms is one
of the priorities listed by the Estrada administration which took
office at the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's predecessor, former president Fidel Ramos, had
pursued to amend the charter in 1997 which he said gave too much
power to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos's supporters stopped the charter change campaign
after being widely accused of trying to allow Ramos to extend his
six-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
