<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Block Pakistani Embassy for Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian security forces on
Friday surrounded the Pakistani embassy here to avoid possible
attacks following the confirmation of the killing of Iranian
diplomats by the Pakistan-backed Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
All the streets leading to the Pakistani embassy have been
blocked and even reporters are not allowed to get access to the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian source told Xinhua that the security measure was
taken after a group of Iranians attacked the embassy Thursday
night. An embassy staff, contacted by Xinhua, confirmed that
attack but refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after the Iranian Foreign Ministry held the
Taliban and Pakistan responsible for the killing of nine Iranian
diplomats in Mazar-e-Sharif, northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban on Thursday confirmed the death of the Iranians and
said they have found the bodies. It had repeatedly denied knowing
the whereabouts of these people missing since August 8.
</P>
<P>
Tehran claimed that 11 diplomats and a correspondent of the
official news agency were captured by the Taliban troops in
Mazar-e-Sherif, a stronghold of the opposition Northern Alliance
which Iran supports.
</P>
<P>
Former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani vowed on Friday
that Iran would take revenge on the Taliban for the killing. "I
promise that the families of the martyrs and Iranian nation would
witness the revenge on the Taliban for martyring our diplomats,"
he said at the Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran would not take any hasty action, but would
carry out a well-designed plan with "clear objectives" at an
appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed over the past few days up to 70,000 troops
along the border with Afghanistan to put more pressure to bear on
the Taliban, and announced another military maneuver there within
days.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say the tragic fate of these diplomats outraged
the Iranian government, making a retaliatory strike or even a
military incursion all the more possible than before.
</P>
<P>
After the Friday prayers, hundreds of Iranians marched along
the street in front of Tehran University, announcing their
readiness to fight against the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
They shouted slogans such as "Death to the Taliban, Death to
(Pakistani Prime Minister) Nawaz Sharif," urging supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who is commander of the armed forces, to
issue war order against the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on Friday
urged the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to take
necessary measures against the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Annan, Kharrazi said that the
Taliban's atrocious act was a clear example of war crimes and
crime against humanity.
</P>
<P>
He had called on the Security Council to put pressures on the
Taliban to hand over the bodies of the killed Iranian diplomats,
to put those responsible on trial and to release all Iranians
captured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
