<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Observers May Leave Angola Next February: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan has said the U.N. observers mission may
postpone its departure and pull out of Angola next February after
implementation of the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol on Angola.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said this in his report submitted to the
U.N. Security Council, according to a report reaching here Friday
from New York where the U.N. headquarters is based.
</P>
<P>
Annan noted that the Angolan peace process may have the last
chance because the term of the U.N. observers mission will expire
on September 15 this year and it can only be extended till
January 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. observers has to end their mission in Angola in
early 1999 no matter whether there is actual progress or not in
implementation of the Protocol by November this year after its
assessment will be made of the peace process," said the U.N.
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
He added in his report that "it will be identified who should
be responsible" for the failure in the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
If there is decisive progress by then, Annan said, the term of
the U.N. mission will be automatically extended so as to exert
its efforts to help achieve the final peace in the war-ravaged
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Annan held President Jonas Savimbi's National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) mainly responsible for the
worsening situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, the peace process is in stalemate basically due to
the retrogression of Savimbi in implementing the Lusaka Peace
Protocol," said the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed at the end of his report that urgent measures
should be taken "in a bid to resume and accompish the (Angolan)
peace process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
