<HEADLINE> China Anticipates Sharp Rise in Offshore Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The China National Offshore
Oil Corp (CNOOC) expects to pump a record 16.5 million tons of
crude oil this year, compared with 16.28 million tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China had produced more than 11 million tons of offshore oil by
the end of August, or some 67.4 percent of the country's planned
output target for 1998, according to CNOOC President Wang Yan.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC has engaged in strenuous efforts to maintain stable
offshore oil production amidst declining worldwide oil prices and
production, said Yan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has place priority on exploration for
offshore oil and has invited extensive foreign cooperation in oil
and gas exploration in the South China, East China and Yellow seas.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC has signed over 130 oil contracts and agreements
with some 70-odd oil companies from 18 countries and regions, with
total overseas investments reaching at 6.4 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yan pointed out the CNOOC has recoreded an astonishing 80
percent success rate for wildcat offshore drilling this year, and
expects to verify additional oil reserves of 130 million tons and
gas reserves totalling 10 billion cu. m. by the end of this year.
</P>
