<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Warn Against World Economic Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Economists, attending a
seminar here, warned Friday that Russia's deepening economic
crisis, if unresolved, would lead the world economies toward a
great depression unseen in decades.
</P>
<P>
Russia serves as "a wake up call" for the world to take action
against a possible global recession, Sa-ard Theerarojanawong, vice
president of Thailand's largest bank's foreign exchange trading
department, said at the seminar entitled "Malaysia, Hong Kong and
Russia -- A New Wave of Crisis".
</P>
<P>
He said such a depression is likely to push down all asset
prices worldwide substantially, so that every nation on every
continent would certainly feel the negative effects.
</P>
<P>
"It would be like a domino effect, one country would fall after
the others," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the importance of the Russian issue in terms of
saving the global economy, Sa-ard said Japan, China and Hong Kong
will also play a greater role in protecting the world from
potential turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He said Japan, the major lender to Asian countries, should get
its banking system on its feet as fast as possible as China and
Hong Kong should show their economic strength and quash all
speculation of a currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
"If the rumors continue, the global economic system will never
recover, and it will be as though we are walking back and forth in
a dark tunnel," he said.
</P>
<P>
An interest rate cut by the U.S. Federal Reserve, he said,
would help prevent capital flowing outside the country into the
U.S. and that would be another way to help save the world from a
depression.
</P>
<P>
Nattapong Samit-Ampaipisarn, vice president of Siam Commercial
Bank's Treasury Department, forecast that there is a more than 50
percent chance that the world will fall victim to a widespread
recession if the markets continue to plump to new depths.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a global economic depression are now mounting, as
emerging markets are expected to trigger a renewed depression,
given that Russia's economic slump coincided with the Asian
economic crises while Latin America has become the latest casualty
of the market turmoil, participants in the seminar noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the United States, considered as the world's
strongest economy, is expected to be hit as the country has huge
investment exposure in Latin American countries while European
nations would also be rocked due to their exposure in Russia, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Person Wounded in Phnom Penh Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Opposition protesters and
government supporters clashed in here Friday, leaving at least one
man wounded in the right leg.
</P>
<P>
The man was shot in the leg when riot policemen moved in and
fired shots to disperse clashing opposition protesters and
government supporters in front the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Riot police, military police and members of the Flying Tigers,
an elite motorcycle police unit, were patroling the city and
trying to clear protesters from the streets.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of protesters gathered around the Independence
Monument about 10 a.m. while hundreds of government supporters
rallied in front of the Royal Palace.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cambodia aggravated following the announcement
of the official results of the July 26 parliament elections.
</P>
<P>
The People's Party led by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen won 64
of the 122 National Assembly seats in the election, which is not
enough for the two-thirds required to form a government alone.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen offered to form a coalition government with opposition
FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party. But his offer was turned down
the opposition who complained about election fraud.
</P>
<P>
The tension between the two camps badly worsened on Monday,
when riot police dispersed demonstrators by force. One was killed
and several wounded in the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
