<HEADLINE> ECOWAS, CPLP to Meet Over G. Bissau Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The ECOWAS Committee of Seven
on Guinea Bissau is scheduled to meet in Abidjan Tuesday with a
team of the Community of Portuguese-Speaking States (CPLP) to
continue their efforts in finding a solution to the Guinea Bissau
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a follow-up of a two-day joint meeting of the
two parties which ended on August 26 with an immediate cease-fire
agreement signed at Praia, Cape Verde, the Nigerian Tribune
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, chiefs of staff and military experts from
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and CPLP
will discuss a review of observance of the cease-fire,
establishing of an observer team, composition of a multi-nation
force and other measures aimed at bringing lasting peace to that
country.
</P>
<P>
Under the cease-fire agreement, the government of Guinea
Bissau and the self-proclaimed military junta, two parties of the
conflict in the tiny west African country, agreed to public
recognition of democratic institutions and legality, freezing of
their respective military positions, and reopening of Osvaldo
Vieira Airport.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS consists of 16 countries including Burkina Faso, Cote
d'Ivoire, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Nigeria and Senegal while CPLP
comprises Angola, Brazil, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Portugal and
Sao Tome and Principe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
