<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces to Take Stern Action Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Armed Forces
(ABRI) will not hesitate to take stern action against
demonstrations which tend to lead to unrest, Defense Minister and
Commander of the ABRI Gen. Wiranto said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI is not willing to allow the acts of some groups of people
to affect more than 200 million Indonesians who want prosperity,
peace and justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto refused to elaborate on what kind of action the ABRI
would take.
</P>
<P>
There are some procedures that the ABRI has to follow and that
they are based on the present regulation in lieu of law on the
freedom of expression, he said after attending a meeting at the
House of Representatives for the presentation of the bill on the
freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
The bill was presented by Justice Minister Muladi to the House
of Representatives for approval.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, a police permit is required if a
demonstration involves more than 50 people. Street protests are
also banned around the presidential palaces, military
installations and other vital locations.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto stressed that the regulation is aimed at securing
national interest.
</P>
<P>
This is not for the interest of the military or the government,
he said, adding that the people, including students, have to
respect the nation's achievements.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to damages caused to the House of
Representatives building after students occupied it last May.
</P>
<P>
Students this week have stepped up protests against the
government for its inability to control the rising prices of
essential commodities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
