<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands in Constitutional Crisis: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Solomon Islands
parliament will meet on September 25 to consider a no-confidence
motion in the government of Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu,
the Australian Associated Press reported (AAP) Friday.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Islands Government Information Director Johnson Honimae
said the date for the special sitting of parliament was announced
by Speaker Paul Tovua Friday, the wire service said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement follows a decision by High Court Chief Justice
John Muria Thursday upholding an order by Governor-General Moses
Pitakaka for an early meeting of parliament to debate a motion of
no confidence in the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu had challenged the governor-general's order, claiming
the governor-general could only call for an early sitting of
parliament in a state of emergency such as a war.
</P>
<P>
Moses issued the order on September 1, saying parliament had to
resolve the issue of the prime minister heading a minority
government.
</P>
<P>
In a radio address to the nation Thursday night, Ulufa'alu said
 the government was considering appealing against the High Court
decision.
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu said the governor-general may have the power to call
a special meeting of parliament to deal with a vote of no
confidence, but calling such a meeting set a precedent with "very
bad side effects".
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the governor-general was only a
ceremonial figure.
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu said the island nation's opposition had given to the
governor-general a list of MPs which purported to show the
opposition had support from 25 MPs while the government had only
24.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said if numerical strength based on a list
was to guide Solomon Islands politics, the government could change
almost every month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
