<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Plunge as Japanese Market Tumbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian bourse
plunged more than two percent Friday after being engulfed by the
negative sentiment which pushed the Japanese share market into a
steep downward spiral, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index tumbled 58 points to finish
at 2,468.3, with most of the damage caused by a late sell-off.
</P>
<P>
Japanese stock prices took their biggest plunge of the year
Friday, shedding more than five percent following the Bank of
Japan's easing of monetary policy this week had failed to buoy the
Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese market was disheartened by developments in the
United States' economic and political arenas and deepening turmoil
in Latin America, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, industrial stocks felt the
blunt of negative sentiment from the Japanese market, with the all
industrials index diving 111.5 points to 4,340.3.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index shed 13.1 points to 957.5, buoyed by
gains in the gold sector on the back of a surge in the price of
the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
The gold index stacked on 61.7 points to 1,015.0, with the spot
price of gold bullion in Sydney surging to a close of 293.75 U.S.
dollars an ounce, up from a close of 286.05 U.S. dollars Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP dropped 28.5 cents to almost 12.16
Australian dollars, global miner Rio Tinto plummeted 66.1 cents to
17.58 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks took most of the battering, with the sector
index shedding 209.5 points to 5,273.6.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank slumped 1.20 Australian dollars, or
5.67 percent, to 19.95 Australian dollars, while the Commonwealth
Bank of Australia slid 77.1 cents to 19.03 Australian dollars,
Westpac bank fell 31 cents to 8.75 Australian dollars and ANZ bank
lost 18 cents to 8.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 321.59 million shares traded for 1.14
billion Australian dollars (682.97 million U.S. dollars), with
falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 646 to 425 and 319
stocks steady.  
</P>
