<HEADLINE> Lebanon Successfully Issues Eurobonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Amid the turmoil in world
financial market, Lebanon has successfully issued Eurobonds worth
350 million U.S. dollars on international debt market, the
National Broadcast Network radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-based financial group Merrill Lynch was charged to
issue the bonds carrying an interest rate of 8.75 percent over a
seven-year period, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The issue, which was launched in London on Tuesday and closed
on Thursday, had met with strong demand. About 90 percent of the
bonds were bought by Lebanese investors, maily banks, and other
Middle East buyers.
</P>
<P>
Due to the financial storms gripping international market,
Lebanese government originally expected to issue at most 250
million dollars. But higher than expected demand raised the figure
to as high as 350 million dollars, a banking source here said.
</P>
<P>
This is the second issue so far this year, after the last
successful 1 billion dollars Eurobond borrowing in March.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese government decided last November to borrow a total of 2
billion dollars on international markets within this year to
restructure national debt, which is predominated by the high
interest rate Lebanese pound.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's national debt at the end of June totaled 15.5
billion dollars, of which nearly 70 percent is internal debt.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources predicted that Lebanon is likely to launch
another borrowing in the world market before the end of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
