<HEADLINE> Australian athletes taking banned drugs doubles in 12 months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of elite
Australian athletes using banned substances almost doubled in 12
months, the Australian Sports Drug Agency said Friday, according
to reports from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Agency chief executive Natalie Howson said 15 athletes from
seven sports tested positive to stimulants, anabolic steroids and
cannabis in 1997-98, up from eight the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Howson said they were among a record 4,313 drug tests
conducted by the agency compared with 3,499 tests in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The athletes testing positive to banned substances were
Newcastle rugby league player Robbie O'Davis and Melbourne
Storm's Rodney Howe and the others came from baseball, soccer,
cycling, motorcycling, water skiing and ice hockey.
</P>
<P>
The penalties ranged from the two-year suspension of a cyclist
for using amphetamines to the 22-week penalties handed out in the
NRL.
</P>
<P>
She said no athletes competing at the Commonwealth Games were
among those who tested positive.
</P>
<P>
Howson added that "The agency is gearing up for the Sydney
2000 Olympics by conducting more tests than ever before." 
</P>
