<HEADLINE> Zambians Opt for Harare Coke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Cheaper imported soft drinks
from Zimbabwe may soon flood the Zambian market following the
recent hiking of the price of soft drinks made in Zambia by
Coca-Cola Company by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Zambians now prefer to buy Zimbabwe-made drinks whose cost
is equivalent to 200 Zambian Kwacha (one U.S. Dollar equals to
2,000 Kwacha), Times of Zambia said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zambian traders of soft drinks threatened to stop buying
minerals from Zambia Bottlers Limited, Zambian manufacturer of
Coca-Cola, preferring instead to source them from Zimbabwe where
they would still be assured of a profit margin after paying duty.
</P>
<P>
Should that happen the future of Zambia Bottlers Limited would
be threatened with the likelihood of the company's closing its
operations in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted company managing director Ian Ackerman as
saying Thursday that closure of the firm was a possibility but
adding quickly that he did not want to think about it.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola raised the price of its products last Monday from
500 to 900 Kwacha each bottle after the Zambian government failed
to honor the agreement concluded with the company last May, under
which the Zambia authorities agreed to reduce the excise duty of
the soft drinks from 20 to five percent while Coca-Cola pledged
to invest 75 million U.S. Dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola said earlier this week it would suspend its plan to
invest on a new production line and scale down its operations in
Zambia, which may make thousands of local workers lose their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, the Zambia Association of Soft Drinks
Manufacturers said the excise duty on soft drinks has crippled
the country's industry.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated its call on the government to revise the May
agreement with Coca-Cola and reduce the tax which has had a
devastating effect on the industry and the Zambian economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
