<HEADLINE> Liberia's Taylor Claims Coup Plot Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has accused the West African peace-keeping force ECOMOG
and the Sierra Leonean government of plotting to overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
Talyor told the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) that
ECOMOG's commander in Sierra Leone, Brigadier-General Maxwell
Khobe had met with Sierra Leonean Deputy Defense Minister, Chief
Sam Hinga Nirman at a barrack in Freetown where they discussed
ways to topple him.
</P>
<P>
Taylor also named Guinean President Alfa Omar Konare as one of
the plotters, claiming that Konare had contacted Nigerian leader
General Abdulsalam Abubakar for permission to use Nigerian troops
in the plot.
</P>
<P>
According to Taylor, the request was refused by Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian president said that under the plot as uncovered
by his government, the plotters had planned to assassinate him in
an all out attack on the executive mansion and the Liberian
Defense Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Taylor also accused Rossevelt Johnson, his rival during the
civil war, of being part of the plot.
</P>
<P>
He said the Liberian government is in possession of a written
evidence to show that Johnson, while in the U.S., had contacted
the Liberian ambassador to the U.S. on the alleged coup plot.
</P>
<P>
In a swift reaction, Brigadier-General Khobe, a Nigerian who
is also the Chief of Defense Staff of Sierra Leone, denied
knowledge of any plot to assassinate or overthrow Taylor.
</P>
<P>
"Liberians are too many to kill Taylor if they want to, it's
not for us or any external body to do that," Khobe told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
Taylor had accused Guinea and the ECOMOG of plotting to
overthrow him in early August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Figures Show Drop in Foreign Trade Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Customs statistics released
today revealed a declining growth rate for China's imports and
exports during the first eight months of this year due to the
influences of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
China's import-export volume hit 205.91 billion US dollars for
the period, up 3.3 percent on the 1997 period. Exports grew 5.5
percent to 118.65 billion US dollars, with imports rising by 0.4
percent to 87.26 billion, according to the data.
</P>
<P>
The nation's accumulated trade surplus stood at 31.38 billion
US dollars, up 22.7 percent over the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the growth rate of China's exports fell by 1.4
percentage points with accompanying 0.3 percentage points drop for
imports when compared to January-July period last year.
</P>
<P>
The exports of processing trade hit 65.67 billion US dollars,
up 0.71 percent, while the imports topped 44.9 billion US dollars,
up 0.6 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's reinstatement of preferential policies
covering imports of equipment and goods for investment purposes
yielded funds totalling 10 billion US dollars during the first
eight months, up 3.2 percent. Experts contend the move further
balanced China's trade activities.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Japan, the Republic of Korea (ROK) and ASEAN
nations continued to decline, with imports from the European
Union and the United States rising by as much as 25 percent by
August.
</P>
<P>
China witnessed a reduction in trade related to primary
products, with exports falling by 13.1 percent to 13.01 billion US
dollars, and imports dropping by 19.1 percent to 14.88 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
China exported finished goods valued at 105.6 billion US
dollars, up 8.3 percent, with imports of related products growing
by 5.7 percent to 72.39 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
