<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda's Son Under Police Probe in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police is probing
Wezi Kaunda, one of Zambia's former president Kenneth Kaunda's
sons, to find out if he is training men abroad to oust President
Frederick Chiluba, a leading independent paper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wezi Kaunda disclosed in Lusaka Thursday that the government
of the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) is
alleging that he is training guerrillas in Angola and South
Africa with a view to returning to topple President Chiluba,
according to The Post.
</P>
<P>
He told the paper that he has received information from
several local and international intelligence sources that the
Zambian government is alleging he is training guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The former army major explained the fact that he has
maintained contacts with military commanders in neighboring
countries does not mean that he is training guerrillas, adding he
is not going to cut those contacts overnight to please the
government.
</P>
<P>
Wezi Kaunda, also chairman of Lusaka District of the
opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP), also
disclosed that on Thursday a combined team of Zambia Police
Criminal Investigations Department officers and a paramilitary
officer swooped on the house of a UNIP ward chairman in the
capital city to try to search for firearms and security forces
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
He, who has had several swoops on his house and offices since
the MMD came into power in 1991, described this as "the beginning
of another Zero Option", the alleged code name of operations by
the UNIP to topple the MMD government.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, security agents raided Wezi Kaunda's office and house
in search of Zero Option documents. He together with some other
senior UNIP officials was subsequently detained but was released
unconditionally after a lengthy trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
