<HEADLINE> Roundup: Multinational Firms Increasing Investment in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Many world-famous multinational
enterprises have greatly increased their investments in China,
according to the ongoing Second China Investment and Trade Fair
in Xiamen, a seaport city in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that more than 1,800 contracts have so
far been signed, including an increasing number of large projects.
</P>
<P>
These large projects have attracted 75.8 percent of the total
investment of 11.5 billion U.S. dollars, and 73.9 percent of the
8.23 billion U.S. dollars of foreign investment already used.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attribute this to the active participation of
such multinational corporations as Motorola, Nokia, Exxon, Mobil,
Sony and Siemens.
</P>
<P>
China implemented a series of preferential policies to
encourage direct foreign investment this year in a bid to counter
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
State councillor Wu Yi said about the fair, "Multinational
enterprises are vital powerhouses promoting the world economy,
and the Chinese government welcomes their investment."
</P>
<P>
To attract more foreign capital, China will further open its
domestic market, promote cooperation between state-run large- and
medium-sized enterprises and foreign companies, and encourage
national firms to establish research centers together with their
foreign counterparts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Multinational Firms Increasing Investment in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that the contractual value of foreign-funded
projects in the first seven months of 1998 reached 28 billion U.S.
dollars, up 7.3 percent from the same 1997 period. Multinationals
accounted for a considerable portion of this.
</P>
<P>
Toshio Miyoshi, chairman of the Board of Matsushica Electric
Works Ltd., said, "We have decided to pump 50 percent of our
overseas investment in China at the beginning of the next century
because we believe China's market is the most stable."
</P>
<P>
To date, 21 of the top 30 American multinational firms are
doing business in China; General Motors alone has 14 projects in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"China will certainly benefit from such enormous direct foreign
investment," according to Jemal-ud-din Kassum, vice-president of
the International Finance Corporation under the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Rubens Ricupero, secretary-general of the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTD), said during a news
conference that China is the most successful example of a country
absorbing direct foreign investment among all developing
countries, and the flow of direct overseas funding into China has
undergone an unprecedented increase in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence in investment prospects in China.
</P>
<P>
According to a worldwide survey conducted by the UNCTD, most of
the world's top 500 companies have no intention of postponing or
canceling direct investment in southeast Asia, and most of them
are even planning to increase such funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
