<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Vows Iran to Avenge Taliban's Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian President
Hashemi Rafsanjani on Friday vowed that Iran will take revenge on
the Afghan Taliban militia for its killing of nine Iranian
diplomats in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani promised to families and relatives of the victims
that Iran will surely do so at the Friday prayers here. The
Taliban confirmed Thursday that the nine Iranian nationals missing
last month have been killed by "renegade forces" and pledged to
punish those responsible.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani told the congregation that Iran has had a detailed
plan, with specific objectives, to avenge the Taliban crime, and
it is going to execute the plan. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed over the past few days up to 70,000 troops
along the border with Afghanistan to put more pressure to bear on
the Taliban for the release of the Iranians taken captive in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Tehran claimed that 11 diplomats and a correspondent of the
official news agency were captured by the Taliban troops taking
over Mazar-e-Sherif, a stronghold of the opposition Northern
Alliance which Iran supports.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban had repeated denied it knew the whereabouts of the
missing Iranians. But the latest confirmation of the tragic fate
of these diplomats outraged the Iranian government, making a
retaliatory strike or even a military incursion all the more
possible than before, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said Iran's policy toward Afghanistan - to let the
Afghan people solve their own problems - remained unchanged and
Tehran still recognizes the government led by ousted President
Burhanuddin Rabbani as the legal government of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who also appeared at the prayers, accused the Taliban,
who drove him out of capital Kabul in 1996, and now won control
over most of Afghanistan and imposed a strict version of Islamic
rule, of "defying all values and principle."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a religious student militia, was reportedly backed
by Pakistan in its swift rise to prominence and sweeping victory
in war-torn Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
