<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Real GDP Drops for Three Straight Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's gross domestic product
(GDP) in the second quarter of this year shrank by 0.8 percent
from the previous quarter in real terms, or an annualized decline
of 3.3 percent, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The contraction marks the third consecutive quarterly fall. It
is the first time that Japan's GDP has declined for three straight
quarters since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption, which accounts for some 60 percent of the
GDP aggregate, fell 0.8 percent, and corporate capital spending,
another engine for growth, declined 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment fell 1 percent, while public investment
increased 0.1 percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
With this data, it has become increasingly difficult for Japan
to achieve the government's target growth rate of 1.9 percent for
the current fiscal year, said Taichi Sakaiya, director general of
the agency.
</P>
<P>
GDP measures the value of goods and services produced within a
nation. Real GDP figures are adjusted for inflation and seasonal
variations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howard Sees Tight Election Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Friday refused to be carried away by an opinion poll
that found support for the opposition dropping, saying, "This is
going to be a tight election and I don't take anything for
granted."
</P>
<P>
The latest AC Nielsen poll published in the Sydney Morning
Herald Friday found that backing for the opposition Australian
Labor Party (ALP) had fallen behind the ruling Australian Liberal
Party and National Party coalition in the early stages of the
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
It said the ALP's primary vote dropped 3 points to 39 percent
while the coalition remained steady at 43 percent. Support for One
Nation Party was static at 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"I read them but I'm not going to comment," Howard said, when
asked if he was buoyed by the poll. "I think there is a long way
to go, we've got three weeks."
</P>
<P>
Australia plans to hold federal election on October 3.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another poll, the Morgan poll, put Labor ahead of
the coalition for the fourth consecutive week and said the ALP
would have won a federal election held last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The poll put support for Labor at 53.3 percent on a two-party
preferred basis, a fall of 2 percent, while support for the
coalition rose two points to 46.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
