<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Friday following the steep drop on Wall Street overnight,
heightening concerns about a global stock decline.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 749.05 points, or 5.11
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 13,916.98.
</P>
<P>
Last-minute bargain-hunting kept the Nikkei index from
finishing below its 12-year closing low of 13,915.63 marked August
28, when Russia's financial crisis spurred a worldwide sell-off of
shares, trader said.
</P>
<P>
While the steep fall in Wall Street overnight triggered the
decline, stocks were also pushed down by the settlement of
September Nikkei index options and futures contracts, which
traders said apparently ended in a negative balance of shares.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 38.43 points or 3.46 percent to
1,071.48.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 1.25 billion
shares, nearly four times the amount traded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outweighed gainers 1,062 to 156, with 84 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar plunged against
the yen on fears for the stability of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 130.76-79 yen at 5 p.m. (local time),
sharply down from 133.75-78 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and from
134.45-55 yen late Thursday in New York. The dollar briefly
dropped to 128.80 yen, its lowest level in Tokyo in five months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
