<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Chairman Addresses China's Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Developing software and
services for an information technology (IT) industry will be
"critical" for China's effort to restructure state-owned
enterprises and modernization drive, according to IBM Chairman and
CEO Louis Gerstner.
</P>
<P>
The IBM executive made the comments today during an address to
over 400 clients, business partners and members of the press. He
also noted that China's existing IT industry is based on hardware
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
He said China is embarking on an extraordinary new stage in
restructuring enterprises and noted the unprecedented
transformation has never before been witnessed in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Gerstner pointed out that developing a software and services IT
industry will be critical for the success of the transformation
effort and serves as the catalyst, foundation and tool for
developing modern management systems.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government should play a key role in
developing the software and service industry. He noted that
contacts with Chinese authorities have revealed their full
awareness that economic reform goes well beyond the structural
alliances of enterprises. "It will require hard work to rework
enterprise systems," according to Gerstner.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for China to be the world's second largest PC
market by the year 2000. China's sales of computer hardware for
1997 exceeded 100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars) and
accounted for 80 percent of the IT market. However, sales of
software and services accounted for a mere 20 percent of the
market.
</P>
<P>
Gerstner pointed out that services account for the major part
of IT industry in the West, with the sales volume for services far
outstripping the figure for software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
IBM, the world's leading IT service provider, recently signed
agreements with China's Ministry of Information Industry (MII) to
introduce Java, the most efficient language for writing software
programs, and for promoting component programming technology to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Gerstner expressed his belief that China offer vast prospects
for electronic information processing. He also noted that the
number of Internet in China has doubled to well over one million
in the past year, and predicted that the number will hit seven
million by 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
