<HEADLINE> 1,400 People to Contest Australia's Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A record of more than 1,400
people will run for Australia's federal parliament in the October
3 election.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) said Friday that
1,106 people had been nominated to run for the House of
Representatives, almost 200 more than the number of candidates in
the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
They will contest 148 seats in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
In the Senate, 329 candidates will contest 40 available seats,
74 more than those who contested the 1996 poll.
</P>
<P>
In Australia's first federal election in 1901, only 172 people
ran for the parliament.
</P>
<P>
New South Wales has the most aspiring politicians this year.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission said 389 people from the state will
contest the 50 House of Representatives seats.
</P>
<P>
Victoria has 289 candidates for 37 seats while Queensland has
192 candidates for 27 seats.
</P>
<P>
In Western Australia, 109 people will fight it out for 14 seats
and in South Australia, 78 people will run for 12 seats.
</P>
<P>
In Tasmania, 27 candidates will contest five seats while 15
candidates will fight for two seats in the Australia Capital
Territory and seven for one seat in the Northern Territory.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the AEC said, the number of people enrolled to vote
at the election had topped 12 million for the first time in the
country, as 12,056,625 Australians had put their names on the roll
when enrollments officially closed on Monday, compared with
11,655,190 electors on the rolls for the 1996 election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
