<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central, Western Regions to Appeal to Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China's resource-rich central
and western region will have more substantial preferential
policies to attract overseas investment, according to a symposium
at the ongoing '98 China Investment and Trade Fair here.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the symposium, Ma Xiuhong, assistant minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that China will
encourage overseas-invested enterprises based in the coastal area
to seek opportunities in the central and western regions of the
country, where a 25 percent overseas partnership will be treated
as an overseas-funded business and enjoy the same preferences.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a larger portion of overseas financing from
international financial institutions and foreign governments will
be funneled to projects in the western region, Ma noted.
</P>
<P>
China's central and western regions include 19 provinces,
regions and cities which boasts two-thirds of the country's
petroleum, natural gas and hydro-power resources, and 91 percent
of its major mine reserves.
</P>
<P>
Their share of overseas investment accounted for 14 percent of
the country's total last year, an increase of 8 percent since
1990. This has been attributed to lower product costs in these
regions, which is causing an increasing number of investors to
shift their focus from the east to the west.
</P>
<P>
There are a range of industries of large potential for overseas
investment, including agriculture, animal husbandry, mining, raw
material processing, infrastructure construction and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that backward infrastructure conditions in the central
and western regions are a major hurdle in attracting overseas
investment. In southern Yunnan Province for example, the railway
transportation capacity totals 10 million tons, in contrast to a
25 million-ton demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
