<HEADLINE> Ugandan Central Bank Rushes to Rescue Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Uganda, the
country's central bank, has rushed to stabilize the Ugandan
Shilling which has been falling drastically fast over the last
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
Wlugembe Musoke, the director of public relations of the bank,
revealed to the press that his bank has intervened, but did not
elaborate on how much the bank has injected in the market,
according to a Monitor newspaper report Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank will intervene as long as it is necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Dollar has for the past few months beaten the
Shilling over the head, with selling quotations jumping from
1,160 Shillings against the Dollar in February to 1,250 Shillings
in July. By Thursday evening, some foreign exchange bureaus were
quoting 1,300 Shillings against the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Some economists blamed the depreciation of this currency to
the government's too much expenditure on non-economic ventures,
the instability in the Great Lakes region and the sharp fall of
coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
This sharp fall of Shilling may affect the country's ability
to service its debts, erode the country's exports on the
international market and hit hard producers of goods which
require a lot of imported raw materials, said Marios Obwona, a
senior economic research fellow with Makerere University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
