<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Worsens Further in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The overall flood situation has
further worsened in the central part of Bangladesh and in and
around the capital city of Dhaka, disrupting the railway link
between the capital and three cities from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Direct railway services between Dhaka and the second largest
city of Chittagong, northeastern and southeastern cities of Sylhet
and Noakhali have been canceled due to the rising of water level
by 20 centimeters in a section, press reports Friday quoted
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the capital is deteriorating further with
inundation of more residential and commercial areas and city
streets while the Dhaka-Narayanganj-Demra (DND) embankment and the
city protection embankment are under continuous threat with the
swelling of waters in the Buriganga, Sitalakhay and Turag rivers.
</P>
<P>
Apart from troops, engineers of the Water Development Board and
other departments concerned are working round the clock to repair
leakage, breaches and cracks in the DND embankment.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation in and around Dhaka city may get worse
during the next 24 hours because of flood waters from the upstream
of major rivers such as the Brahmaputra, Ganges and Meghna and
abnormal rise of tides in the Meghna estuary, according to the
Flood Forecasting and Warning Center.
</P>
<P>
In Dhaka, the southern half of the road connecting the
inter-city bus terminal with the city has been under knee-deep
water at two points near the terminal and flood water may cross
the road divider at any time.
</P>
<P>
The gushing flood waters have already entered the premises of
several foreign missions, which are located in the city's
northeastern areas of Gulshan, Banani and Baridhara.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commission has asked all its officials to
evacuate their children while the Australian Embassy urged its
members to evacuate their families.
</P>
<P>
The flood, which has lasted for more than two months, has
already affected about 30 million people in 47 of the country's 64
districts, with the flood-related death toll reaching 843 so far,
according to the Relief Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
