<HEADLINE> Clinton Eager to Meet Nigerian Leader at UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has expressed his eagerness to meet with Nigerian Head of State
General Abdusalam Abubakar during the 53rd session of the General
Assembly of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Nigeria William Twadell conveyed Clinton's
invitation in Abuja Thursday, when he met Abubakar who is
scheduled to attend the U.N. General Assembly Monday.
</P>
<P>
Twadell reportedly briefed the Nigerian leader on the reaction
of the U.S. government to the measures so far taken in the
Nigerian democracy process.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador assured that his government's position on the
positive development in Nigeria would be soon given practical
expression in many areas of joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Abubakar expressed satisfaction with the
positive reaction of the international community, especially the
U.S. and the European Union to the measures taken by him to
establish a united, stable and prosperous democratic polity in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the measures being adopted by his government
were consistent with the aspirations of Nigerians for democracy
which has become a universal phenomenon too strong to ignore.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Nigerian relations got soured in 1995 when the U.S.
and Western world slammed sanctions on Nigeria after former
government of late General Sani Abacha hanged author Ken
Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists on charges of
murder.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations between the two countries began to improve
soon after Abubakar taking office in June following the sudden
death of Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has shown his commitment to democratize Nigeria in
his moves of releasing all political detainees, scraping the
discredited transition program of his predecessor and announcing
a new transition process, by which the military is bound to
return to barracks in May next year.  
</P>
