<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Issues Take Center Stage in Ross' Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- As U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross' mission continues, his shuttles between Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators indicate that security issues take the
center stage in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Since his return to the region Wednesday, Ross has held two
rounds of talks with the Palestinians - one with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat in Ramallah Wednesday, another with
Palestinian negotiators Abu Ala, Abu Mazen and Saeb Erekat here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ross also met with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and President Ezer Weizman here Thursday, and held another meeting
with Netanyahu, together with his four inner cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Those discussions showed that both the Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators focused their attention on the the U.S. proposal as a
package, looking at the specifics of such key issues as security
cooperation, along with Israel's troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
For Israel, security has become the key issue hindering the
peace process. It insisted that it will make no deal to advance
the process or accept the U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank in the second stage redeployment
until the Palestinian side does more to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side gave a different explanation of this
issue. Erekat said on Thursday that for Israeli-palestinian
security cooperation, there was a U.S. brokered Memorandum of
Understanding (MOU) that won the acceptance of security officials
from all sides last December, but Netanyahu scuttled it, opposing
the reference that required equal enforcement against extremism on
both Israeli and Palestinian sides.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation must be
based on the MOU and Israel's acceptance of the MOU is the basis
for further security cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He also insisted that Israel must accept "reciprocal
obligations on security" by enforcing the law against Israeli
extremists who kill Palestinians and afterwards are let out from
prison.
</P>
<P>
Reaching an agreement on this issue may take some time, but
the shooting and killing incidents continue. Israeli soldiers
shot to death two "Palestinian terrorists" in Hebron Thursday,
clamping a closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip starting Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Kamale Nadher, a 41-year-old Palestinian women shot with a
rubber bullet by Israeli police Saturday at the Shufat Refugee
camp in northern Jerusalem, died and buried Thursday, leaving
four children behind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
