<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 08:30 GMT, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Thursday
night urged the United Nations Security Council to show its
reaction to the killing of Iranian diplomats by the Afghan Taliban
militia. (Iran-UN-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France started to enforce a European Union ban on the
takeoff and landing of Yugoslav airline JAT planes on midnight
Thursday in protest against the growing tension in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret
announced that the last JAT flight had left Paris and the ban
would not apply to emergency landings and takeoffs or JAT planes
flying through French air space. (France-Yugoslavia-Flight Ban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- The Cuban government Thursday said it would refuse
any humanitarian aid from the United States government despite a
drought in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after the United Nations requested 20.5
million U.S. dollars in food aid for 615,000 Cubans affected by
drought, which the U.S. State Department is considering.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman Alejandro Gonzalez said that
the U.N. World Food Program had announced a 20-million dollar aid
package after five provinces in the eastern part of the island
were badly hit by drought. (Cuba-Rejection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- Hungary fully supports the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's military action plan aimed at settling the Kosovo
crisis, Foreign Ministry spokesman Horvath Gabor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the Serb security forces should immediately end their
operations against Kosovo residents, which, he said, "have so far
brought about serious humanitarian and political consequences."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said, the Kosovo armed forces should also
halt their military actions. (Hungary-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada has ruled out the
adoption of foreign exchange controls akin to those imposed last
week by Malaysia to ward off anti-currency attacks.
</P>
<P>
A presidential press release Friday quoted the president as
saying the adoption of foreign exchange controls might only spawn
more speculative attacks on the Philippine peso and, worse,
restore a dollar black market similar to the one that hit the
country in the past. (Philippines-Currency Control)  
</P>
