<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Chip Sales Down 17 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide semiconductor
sales in July fell 17 percent from the same month last year,
according to a report released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chip sales dropped to 9.66 billion U.S. dollars, compared to
11.65 billion dollars in July last year, said the U.S.
Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA) in the report.
</P>
<P>
SIA said that the drop was mainly due to continued economic
turmoil in Japan, whose chip sales plunged 30.2 percent in July,
and the oversupply of memory chips in world markets.
</P>
<P>
Sales in all major world markets declined in July from year-ago
totals.
</P>
<P>
Sales on the American market fell from 3.85 billion dollars to
3.20 billion dollars and Asia-Pacific slipped from 2.54 billion
dollars to 2.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Europe's sales held up better than other regions, with revenues
falling just 3.9 percent to 2.22 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"A positive sign in the marketplace is that personal computer
sales continue to grow," the SIA report said. "The oversupply of
some semiconductor products has driven down the average selling
price of applications, but pricing will modify as demand balances
with capacity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
