<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Kenyans Stranded on Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- About 200 Kenyans were
stranded on Lake Victoria for more than eight hours after the
three boats carrying them were trapped in thick mats of the water
hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
The three boats left Homa Bay, western Kenya, at around 10:00
a.m. Wednesday for various beaches along the Kenyan side of the
lake, but advancing mats of the weed blocked their paths,
eyewitnesses were quoted by Friday's Daily Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The passengers, most of them are women and children, were
still stranded in the lake until later afternoon. They shouted
for help and asked for food and water, which could not be
delivered to them.
</P>
<P>
But at around 6:30 p.m. on the day, strong winds pushed away
the weed and the three boats continued on their way.
</P>
<P>
A sentry at the Homa Bay pier said the passengers would have
no alternative but to sit in the boats and pray that strong winds
push away the weed, which has paralyzed transport and fishing in
the lake for years.
</P>
<P>
Incidents of boats getting trapped in the weed, he explained,
had become a common occurrence since the weed drifted from Kisumu
Port to beaches in Homa Bay and Rachuonyo districts three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the people living around the lake use boats as
the only means of transport since the Kenya Railways Corporation
withdrew passenger steamers because of the hyacinth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 08:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Broad Based Afghan Government Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Pakistan have
agreed that only the establishment of a broad based government in
Afghanistan can bring peace to the war-stricken country, a senior
Turkish official said.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News newspaper on Friday quoted the official, who
declined to be named, as saying that both Turkey and Pakistan are
concerned about the worsening situation there.
</P>
<P>
The official said that a high-level Turkish delegation headed
by Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Korkmaz Haktanir recently held
discussions with Pakistani officials in Islamabad on the latest
developments in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that both sides are extremely uneasy about the
attitude of the Taliban, which they feel reflects "a medieval
mentality".
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a student militia said to have Pakistani backing,
has won control over most of Afghanistan and imposed a strict form
of Islamic rule there.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has realized that the Taliban is bent
on "fighting to the bitter end" and this is a further source of
concern, The Turkish official added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has stated that it will closely follow the developments
in Afghanistan and appoint a special "coordination ambassador" to
handle the matter.
</P>
<P>
Leading Afghan opposition figures, such as ousted President
Burhanuddin Rabbani, General Rashid Dostum and Abdulmalik Khan
have visited Ankara in recent weeks to discuss with Turkish
officials the current situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Turkey hates to see the domination of the Taliban in
Afghanistan for fear that an Islamic regime would export its
extremism to the neighboring Muslim countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Health Officials Urge More Funding to Fight Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. health officials
Thursday urged the federal government to allocate 200 million
U.S. dollars a year to the Center for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDCP) for battles against diseases.
</P>
<P>
They said that since 1994 the center has uncovered outbreaks of
illnesses in its programs conducted in seven states, but the
government provided only about a third of the requested money.
</P>
<P>
The center is conducting a four-year program to identify new
and re-emerging killer diseases before they cause major outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
CDCP officials said several new threats, such as bird flu and
mad cow disease, have been reported since 1994.
</P>
<P>
"The threats have not gone away," warned Dr. James Hughes,
director of CDCP's National Center for Infectious Diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
