<HEADLINE> African Athletes Vow to Grab Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- African athletes have
vowed to show the world they are a powerhouse when the 8th
Athletics World Cup opens Friday at Johannesburg Stadium.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 athletics stars from around the globe have
arrived at Johannesburg, who will compete for eight teams from
different continents in the quadrennial athletics showpiece.
</P>
<P>
The African men's team, two-time defending World Cup champions
and one of the favorites to take this year's World Cup team
trophy, recently renamed Nelson Mandela Trophy, is oozing with
confidence.
</P>
<P>
World 3,000m steeplechase record holder Bernard Barmasai
didn't mince his words when he promised Africa a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
"I am in great shape and I promise you nothing else but a
gold. I will be doing it for Africa in Africa," he told local
journalists.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai's countryman and current world 5,000m champion Daniel
Komen also promised to score gold in the first World Cup staged
on African soil.
</P>
<P>
Noting his event would be the second track event Friday,
Zambian Samuel Matete predicted he would be the first medalist of
the team.
</P>
<P>
"I don't expect the race to be very fast. We are all tired
after a long season but I will give it a big effort to contribute
to the defense of our title, and that includes winning a medal,"
Matete said.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of competition, the African men's team
expects five medals, which includes two golds - from Komen in the
5,000m and Kenyan Japhet Kimutai in the 800m.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the African women's team, which finished fourth in
last World Cup in 1994, is hoping to get into the top three this
time. 
</P>
