<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Poplar Tree Sets New Growth Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A poplar tree planted 21
years ago in east China's Jiangsu Province has reached a height of
40 meters and has a diameter of 88 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate for the tree, an Italian Poplar, has set a new
maturation record in China. Experts from Canada, Italy and
Japan have conducted studies to determine factors leading to the
rapid maturation process.
</P>
<P>
The tree, the tallest in China, was planted at the Zhangxu Tree
Nursery in Suining County, Jiangsu Province, in 1976. The tree was
3.1 meter tall when planted.
</P>
<P>
The original sapling withered and was cut in the spring of
1977. The existing tree, which sprouted from the remaining stump,
grew to a height of 4.32 meters and had a diameter of 4.7 cm. by
1978. The following year the tree reached a height of 8.6 meters
and had a diameter of 16 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The Poplar is still growing and the trunk diameter increases by
as much as one cm. annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
