<HEADLINE> Israel Seals off West Bank, Gaza Strip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel has clamped a
closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip beginning Friday morning
and declared a nationwide security alert following the killing of
two Palestinian militants Thursday night by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army announced the decision Thursday night after
the two armed Palestinians were shot dead in an exchange of fire
with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers went to the house of the Palestinians after
hearing sounds of explosions and gunshots, and then clashed with
them.
</P>
<P>
After the seal-off went into effect at 4:00 a.m., all
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza were not allowed to enter
Israel. Meanwhile, Israeli army said its forces were put on extra
high alert, roadblocks were beefed up and reinforcements have been
dispatched.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted the army as saying the two Palestinians
have been identified as Imad Awadallah and his brother, both
members of militant resistance group Hamas. The army said it had
found "a lot of weapons" following a search of their house.
</P>
<P>
Imad Awadallah, considered as one of the top four Hamas
military activists, escaped from a Palestinian jail in Hebron
last month after a four-month imprisonment on suspicion of
shooting dead Hamas master bomb-maker Muhei Sharif in March.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army said Imad and his brother were on their way to
carry out a major attack and the clash took place in an area under
full Israeli security control. But the exact location was kept
secret.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, a bus carrying Israeli religious students to
another West Bank town of Nablus was hit by gunfires but no one
was injured.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Friday morning that Hamas officials in
Gaza had pledged to take revenge on the killing of the two
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The closure was declared as U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross
was on a renewed mission here trying to bridge the gap between
Israel and the Palestinians over the long overdue Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
