<HEADLINE> U.S. Company to Control Power New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- UtiliCorp United, a U.S.
power company, has decided to buy Power New Zealand shares from
Mercury Energy and WEL Energy in order to control one of the
biggest
private-run electricity-generating companies in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Friday that
the move would allow UtiliCorp to increase its stake in Power New
Zealand from 37.5 percent to 78.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
UtiliCorp's offer price of 6.625 NZ dollars a share valued
Mercury's 33.2 percent Power New Zealand holding at 333.2 million
NZ
dollars (about 170 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The same price applied to WEL energy's 7.9 percent Power New
Zealand stake, valued at 79.7 million NZ dollars (40.5 million
U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
After the transactions, the Power New Zealand shareholding
would
comprise 78.6 percent held by UtiliCorp, 10.7 percent by the Power

New Zealand Shareholder Society, 9 percent by the public and 1.7
percent under the employee share ownership plan.
</P>
<P>
The NZPA quoted Mercury Energy chief executive Patrick Strange
as
saying the proposed agreement would provide "a practical and
mutually
beneficial outcome to what has become long-running ownership
struggle."
</P>
<P>
He added that the sales and purchases of shares would also help

"clarify issues of ownership and control."
</P>
<P>
Power New Zealand acting chairman Graeme Hawkins was quoted as
saying the deal would "benefit his company by streamlining
governance
issues." 
</P>
</TEXT>
