<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Terms of Trade Worsen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's terms of
trade
worsened in the second quarter of this year, according to figures

released recently by Statistics New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
An index, produced by Statistics New Zealand to measure the
relative value of exports and imports, declined by 4.1 percent in
the
second quarter and 1.2 percent in the year ending June 1998.
</P>
<P>
This was because export prices eased and import prices rose,
producing an overall worsening in the terms of trade.
</P>
<P>
The export price index, which feeds into the terms of trade
index,
eased 0.6 percent in the second quarter, after three quarterly
rises.
The import price index rose by 3.5 percent at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand dollar fell 4.4 percent in the second quarter
and
13.9 percent in the year ending June 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, New Zealand wool prices went down
by
3.3 percent in the second quarter because of lower demand from
Asia.
Other significant falls in export prices occurred in chemicals and

related products, non-fuel crude materials, non-food manufactured
goods and petrol and petrol products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
