<HEADLINE> Weak Asian Demand Cuts Port of Seattle's Grain Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Weak demand from Asia has
cut grain exports through the Port of Seattle to less than half
the volume of a year ago, Seattle Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the port had exported 1.04 million metric
tons of grain, a 52 percent drop from the 2.16 million metric tons
logged during the same seven-month period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Washington State exported 5.6
billion U.S. dollars worth of agricultural goods to Asian
countries in 1996. For 1997, the state Agriculture Department
estimated Asian shipments fell by 478 million dollars because of
the region's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Northwest agriculture had been one of the big
beneficiaries from Asia's booming economies. Its wheat was the
premier ingredient in some noodles, breads, fancy cakes and other
delicacies popular in some Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Wheat Commission estimates that 60 percent to 80
percent of the state's wheat went to Asia during the latter's
booming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
