<HEADLINE> Maize Harvest to Rise by 6.5 Percent in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's maize harvest is set
to increase by 6.5 percent to 2.3 million tons from an annual
average of 2.16 million tons in the past six years, according to
the latest data from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture estimates indicate that stocks of
maize are close to 720,000 tons, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
There are no reserve stocks at present, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has recommended that the National Strategic Grain
Reserve stocks be replenished to the normal level of 270,000 tons
and a national food security office be set up to monitor domestic
food stocks, imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
Maize harvesting had been completed in the lower, drier areas
of five out of all the eight provinces -- Coast, Eastern,
Central, Nyanza and Western.
</P>
<P>
In the upper-lying areas of the east African country, the
exercise is still in progress.
</P>
<P>
A significant price reduction has occurred in the rural
markets of the early harvesting districts while prices have
remained stable in most urban markets in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
