<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Take Interest in Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- As the gap between
urban and rural areas in China narrows, books are becoming
more popular among farmers.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 500,000 rural households in northern China's Hebei
Province shows that each of these households has at least 300
books and subscribes to two newspapers.
</P>
<P>
"Books are very useful," said Zhang Guizhen of Beijiao Village
in the suburbs of Shijiazhuang City in Hebei Province, adding that
she earned more than 10,000 yuan by raising pigs and cattle after
reading some books on the subject.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers in the more wealthy rural areas in south China
have begun to show an interest in English. "English corners" and
"English salons" are now appearing in some villages.
</P>
<P>
In Shaanxi and Hebei provinces, some farmers are able to talk
fluently with foreign visitors in English or Japanese while
engaging in tourism services.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Zhejiang Province, some fishermen take
popular English reading material with them while fishing on the open
sea, and read in their spare time.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Lichuan often fishes in the Atlantic Ocean and says he
could communicate with foreign fishermen after he had
learned some English.
</P>
<P>
"English is very helpful when we need to cooperate with foreign
counterparts in fishing," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese farmers' enthusiasm to pursue knowledge results in
improving educational levels for rural areas and helps farmers earn
more money, said an official from the Chinese Agriculture
Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
