<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Rules Out Foreign Exchange Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ruled out the adoption of foreign exchange controls
akin to those imposed last week by Malaysia to ward off
anti-currency attacks.
</P>
<P>
A presidential press release Friday quoted the president as
saying the adoption of foreign exchange controls might only spawn
more speculative attacks on the Philippine peso and, worse,
restore a dollar black market similar to the one that hit the
country in the past.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Malaysian government pegged its currency, the
ringgit, to a fixed exchange rate against the U.S. dollar and
imposed other foreign exchange controls in a bid to shield the
country's markets from foreign speculators.
</P>
<P>
Estrada told the Manila Overseas Press Club Thursday night that
Malaysian-style currency restrictions are not needed because "we
are more economically stable than Malaysia today."
</P>
<P>
He said, moreover, that his economic and budget managers have
already put in place four measures to parry anti-currency attacks
fueled by the deepening Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
To dampen anti-peso attacks, Estrada said, the government has
already initiated an austerity or belt-tightening program along
with measures to prune the budget deficit, cut wanton public
spending and upgrade tax collection.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe we have to follow the steps of Prime Minister
Mahathir (Mohamad). We are more economically stable than Malaysia
today. We don't need currency controls because it might trigger
more speculative attacks on the peso," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that there is no need for currency controls because
"the after-effect of currency controls might even be the rise of a
black market on dollars. We have experienced that before."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
