<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sand-Dredging Ban Imposed on Part of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
at the lower reaches of the Yangtze River has imposed a sand
dredging ban in its 425-kilometer-long section of the river.
</P>
<P>
An official with the provincial people's congress said the ban
is being imposed to meet with anti-flood requirements and ensure
river stability.
</P>
<P>
A regulation just adopted by the provincial people's congress
stipulates that anyone violating the ban will have their
sand-dredgers confiscated and be subject to fines of between
10,000 yuan (1,200 U.S. dollars) and 100,000 yuan (12,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The judicial department will investigate into the criminal
responsibility of those whose sand dredging causes serious damage
to the river embankment, the local regulation says.
</P>
<P>
Excessive sand dredging in Jiangsu Province in the past few
years has resulted in several river-bank collapses, threatening
shipping safety along the Yangtze and the safe operation of the
river wharves.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 large- and medium-sized wharves have been built
along the Yangtze at Jiangsu Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 07:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for U.N. Reaction Taliban's Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi Thursday night urged the United Nations Security
Council to show its reaction to the killing of Iranian diplomats
by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Kharrazi made the
call in a telephone conversation with chairman of the Security
Council. He deemed the Taliban's killing as "an obvious crime of
war against human being," and urged the Security Council should
take responsibility to tackle the war crime.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also called on the Security Council to put pressure on
the Taliban to hand over the bodies of the killed Iranian
diplomats, to put the killers on trial and to release all Iranians
captured by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban confirmed on Thursday that nine of the 11 Iranian
diplomats and an IRNA correspondent missing in northern
Afghanistan have been killed by "renegade forces," and their
bodies have been found.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian ambassador to the U.N. Hadi Husseinian on
Thursday presented a letter of the Iranian government to
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, asking for the arrest and
extradition of those responsible to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government expresses surprise and anger to such a
"crime which showed the Taliban's insult to the internationally
recognized norms and laws, and its ignorance to the fundamental
principles of the human being," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The letter called on the U.N. Security Council to hold
emergency meeting to discuss the issue and take urgent and
necessary measures.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the killing of Iranian diplomats was an
evident insult and violation of Iran's sovereignty by the
Taliban, who should bear the consequences of their behaviors.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed over the past few days up to 70,000 troops
along the border with Afghanistan to put more pressure on the
Taliban, and analysts say an Iranian retaliatory military strike
or even an incursion can not be excluded.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on Thursday issued a statement condemning
the Taliban for killing Iranian diplomats and called the act a
violation of international laws.
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on the Taliban to immediately
release other Iranians it held, and expressed the hope that Afghan
warring parties could solve the crisis through peaceful means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
