<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Province Bans Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Logging of natural forests in
the Jinsha River Valley, southern China's Yunnan Province, will be
illegal as of October 1.
</P>
<P>
Local sources indicate the ban on logging will be carried out
in conjuction with the initiation of an extensive afforestation
program.
</P>
<P>
Jinsha River, a tributary in the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River, flows through 73 Yunnan cities and counties. The
mountainous valley is home to millions of hectares of forest and
various rare animal and plant species.
</P>
<P>
Forest coverage has dwindled rapidly since the 1960s due to
excessive logging which has created serious erosion and harmed
farmland. The fact that over 260 million tons of soil and sand
which flow from the valley into the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River on an annual basis has at least in part been
blamed for heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
The constantly deteriorating natural environment, especially
this summer's devastating floods, has placed experts and
provincial leaders on a high state of alert.
</P>
<P>
The province will adopt measures to protect forests covering
7.49 millions hectares, carry out afforestation projects on an
additional 3.5 million hectares, designate over 700,000 hectares
of hillside forests as protected areas and reforest 800,000
hectares in the valley. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Tries to Deal with Regional Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has
initiated some measures in an effort to lessen the impact of the
regional financial and monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The New Light of Myanmar said in an editorial on Friday that
the government is encouraging the increase of production in goods
and services while taking austerity measures by cutting state
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The government is also giving more attention to increasing
exports while restricting non-essential imports and implementing a
more efficient taxation system.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is watching with great concern the development in the
financial and exchange markets in the region, the editorial said,
adding there has been a serious pressure on the currencies of the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the impact on Myanmar of the currency turmoil in
the region has been slight up till now, it said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Myanmar feels that the existing inequitable and
outdated international monetary and financial system needs a
comprehensive reform, the editorial said, voicing support for the
call made for the first time in 1983 at the New Delhi Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) Summit to convene an international conference on
money and finance for development in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's support for the move was expressed by the country's
Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw when he attended the NAM Summit held
in Durban, South Africa, early this month.
</P>
<P>
The regional financial crisis prompted a rise in commodity
prices and a drop in the exchange rate of the Myanmar currency
Kyat against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the financial storm affected Myanmar's
foreign trade and investment to some extent, bringing about a
trade deficit of 1.24 billion dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March and a fall of 1 billion dollars in foreign
investment in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The crisis is also seen as a factor which hindered Myanmar's
endeavors to achieve the targeted growth of 6.4 percent in its
gross domestic product in 1997-98, which increased by only 4.6
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Tax Aimed at Speculator, Not Public: Thai Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Ministry of
Thailand has urged the general public to accept the proposed land
tax increases, saying they are aimed mainly at land speculators
and not ordinary people, the Bangkok Post said Friday.
</P>
<P>
People who buy land and buildings for speculative purposes
would be hardest hit by the changes, as the tax would be doubled
every three years on undeveloped land, the newspaper quoting
Supachai Pisitvanich, the ministry's permanent secretary as
saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the new land taxation, there will be five classes
of tax rates, with each class divided into three categories:
highly developed, intermediate, and underdeveloped.
</P>
<P>
A highly developed area in class 1 would face the highest tax
rate, 0.095 percent of appraised value. Underdeveloped areas in
class 5 would be charged the lowest rate, 0.025 percent.
</P>
<P>
Property location will determine the taxation class and Bangkok
alone will be placed in class 1.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Supachai explained, a person who owned one Rai (0.16
hectare) of highly-developed property in Bangkok, appraised at 1
million baht (25,000 U.S. dollars), would pay 950 baht (23.75
dollars) a year in tax.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the burden of the public, tax increases proposed
for land and buildings would be phased in over up to five years.
</P>
<P>
The five-year phase-in would apply to taxpayers with bills of
1,000 baht (25 dollars) or more.
</P>
<P>
For example, the owner of a prime site in central Bangkok could
be paying as little as 2,500 baht (62.5 dollars) a year at
present.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, the tax would jump to nearly 30,000 baht
(750 dollars). The taxpayer could double his payments in the first
three years, to 5,000, 10,000 and 20,000 baht (125, 250 and 500
dollars), and begin paying 30,000 baht in the subsequent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices
continued to fall this week with prices at auctions in Sydney and
Adelaide dropping by close to two percent on average, and the
market is expected to come under severe pressure next week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said in its
weekly report Friday that the eastern market indicator fell 10
cents to end the week at 527 Australian cents a kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
"Similar falls of 10 cents occurred in both the northern and
southern region indicators which saw them finish at 533 and 521
cents/kilogram clean respectively," ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
The western region indicator remained at 496 cents per kilogram
clean with no sale in Fremantle, a coastal city in western
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 56,388 bales were offered for sale with 14 percent
passed in comprising 12.3 percent in Sydney and 15.6 percent in
Adelaide, capital of South Australian state.
</P>
<P>
ACWE said there had been no change in the global demand
situation which continued to be the dominant factor for the
current disappointing level of prices.
</P>
<P>
"In this environment, the market is expected to come under
further severe pressure next week where the rostered offering is
more than double the quantity offered this week," ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
Next week 117,000 bales will be up for sale in Sydney,
Melbourne and Fremantle, the largest offering of the season to
date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
