<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds Railway, Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China has accelerated the
pace of railway and highway construction this year in a bid to
give impetus to increasing the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The central government recently added another 4.2 billion yuan
(506 million U.S. dollars) to railway investment, bringing the
total for this year to 53 billion yuan (6.39 billion
U.S. dollars). An investment of 41.3 billion yuan (4.98 billion
U.S. dollars) will be put into the construction of large- and
medium-sized projects, laying 1,876 kilometers of railroad tracks,
building 1,210 kilometers of new rail lines, 575 kilometers of
double-track lines, and 1,091 kilometers of electric railways.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21.76 billion yuan (2.62 billion U.S. dollars) was
invested in 39 large- and medium-sized projects and a dozen new
projects by the end of August. The Ministry of Railways noted that
work in the next four months will exceed that of the past eight
months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts are being made to intensify the construction
of 16 priority projects, including the double-track line on the
southern section of the Beijing-Kowloon railway, and the
electrification of the Chengdu-Kunming railway, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Communications said that investment in highway
construction reached 86.2 billion yuan (10.39 billion
U.S. dollars) in the past eight months, a jump of 82 percent over
the same 1997 period. At present, 3.04 million Chinese are
employed in highway construction.
</P>
<P>
The ministry scheduled 319 highway projects for this year to a
total length of 38,500 kilometers, including 12,700 expressways
and 4,372 kilometers of high-grade highways.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that 0.31 percentage points will be added to
the growth of the GDP by investing 180 billion yuan (21.69 billion
U.S. dollars) in highway construction this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
