<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide PC Sales Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide personal
computer (PC) sales are expected to grow 12.2 percent for the
second half of 1998 despite the financial instability in Asia and
Russia, according to a report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
PC sales grew 11 percent last quarter, reflecting a "warming"
of the global market, said the U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
Most PC vendors have resolved the inventory gluts which led to
fire-sale prices and shrinking profit margins in the first half of
the year, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Despite ongoing currency problems in Asian and eastern European
markets, PC sales appear to be stabilizing. IDC expects the market
to perform better in the next six months with improved demand for
low-cost and portable PCs.
</P>
<P>
While the market signals a possible bright future, IDC is still
worried that the spread of global economic problems might bring a
decline in PC demand.
</P>
<P>
IDC described western Europe as a promising market, driven by
heightened interest in the Internet, low-cost PCs as well as
greater focus on the region by major global brands.
</P>
<P>
U.S. growth this quarter is pegged at 14 percent based on the
continued strength of the low-cost PC market, healthy consumer
demand and a more vibrant portable computer segment, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
However, sales in the Asia-Pacific region (excluding Japan) are
forecast to fall three percent this quarter and nearly two percent
for the entire year. Japan is expected to decline four percent
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last August: Hottest Month on Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 10 (Xinhua) -- August was not only
the hottest month on record, but also the eighth month in a row to
set a new average high temperature worldwide, according to a
report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The average global temperature for August was 61.4 degrees
Fahrenheit, breaking the previous record of 61.1 degrees set in
1997, and was 1.3 degrees above the long-term average of 60.1 for
August, the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
(USNOAA) reported.
</P>
<P>
For the year to date, according to USNOAA report, the average
global temperature of 58.5 degrees Fahrenheit was also 1.3 degrees
above the long-term average of 57.2.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, the year 1934 had the warmest January
through August, with average temperature of a record 56.9 degrees
Fahrenheit. This year, the average temperature between January and
August was 56.2 degrees, 1.9 degrees above the normal average
temperature of 54.3 for the same period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned average temperatures are based on data from
1880 to 1997, according to the National Climatic Data Center, the
USNOAA's record-keeping division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
