<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Pilots Strike to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators for Northwest
Airlines and its pilots reached an agreement Thursday on a deal,
paving the way for an end to the pilots strike that has grounded
the U.S. airline for 13 days.
</P>
<P>
"I think the strike is over," President Bill Clinton announced
at the White House after speaking by phone with leaders from the
pilots' union and the company.
</P>
<P>
The president called union president J. Randolph Babbitt and
Northwest chief executive John Dasburg as the parties were in the
final phase of talks and urged them to "get it done and to get
back to work as soon as possible", an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
But Northwest's 6,100 pilots will remain on strike until at
least Saturday, when the Airline Pilots Association's executive
board will meet to consider the proposal. They will either approve
it or send it to the striking pilots for vote.
</P>
<P>
However, the company began calling ground workers back from
being laid off.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came during overnight negotiations, as the
National Mediation Board's Maggie Jacobsen kept discussions going
until 4 a.m. (local time) Thursday. Bruce Lindsey, one of
Clinton's top advisers, also helped push the talks toward
agreement.
</P>
<P>
No details of the agreement were disclosed, but the two parties
have resolved major differences and they were working on details
of when the pilots would return to work, an Associated Press
report said.
</P>
<P>
The pilots began their strike on August 28, seeking a 14
percent salary increase over three years, while Northwest offered
nine percent over four years.
</P>
<P>
The strike, the longest against a U.S. airline since 1989,
forced Northwest to cancel all its 1,700 daily flights and lay off
about 28,300 non-striking employees. It was estimated that the
strike has caused the airline a loss of more than 300 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
