<HEADLINE> Air Canada and Pilots Reach Tentative Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada and its striking
pilots reached a tentative agreement Thursday night to end a
nine-day strike.
</P>
<P>
The 2,100 pilots of Canada's largest airline are expected to
vote on the proposed contract in a ratification ballot to be held
over the next three days.
</P>
<P>
"Once Air Canada pilots have ratified the agreement, the
airline will begin phasing in operations with 24 hours," the
airline said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Service would resume to most destinations within three to four
days once aircraft are repositioned and crews flown in to operate
flights," the airline said.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which began at midnight, September 1, was centered
on pilots' wage increases. The pilots demanded a 12 percent
increase over two years while the airline agreed only to nine
percent.
</P>
<P>
Details of Thursday's tentative agreement will not be released
until the pilots are briefed, according to the Air Canada Pilots
Association.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a long road, but I am delighted to have secured a
tentative agreement," said Jean-Marc Belanger, chairman of the
association.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good deal. It's a fair deal. But perhaps even more
important for the majority of our pilots, it's a deal that holds
real improvements in our working conditions and the rules we live
by," Belanger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
