<HEADLINE> U.S. High-Tech Exports to China Up 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States increased
its high-tech exports to China by 53 percent in the first half of
1998, the American Electronics Association (AEA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China, where U.S. exports of computers, semiconductors and
consumer electronics grew by 497 million U.S. dollars to 1.43
billion dollars, was a notable exception in Asian markets, AEA
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But exports to other Asian countries fell by 3.74 billion
dollars, 12 percent down from the same period in 1997, as a result
of economic crisis, with a decline of 64 percent to Indonesia, 37
percent to South Korea, 26 percent to Thailand and 14 percent to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
U.S. high-tech or electronics exports totalled 81.9 billion
dollars in the first half of this year, 311 million dollars less
than the corresponding period last year. 
</P>
