<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hongqiao Airport Returns to Normal after Forced Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hongqiao Airport in
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, resumed normal
operation early this morning after a Chinese passenger plane made
an emergency landing at 23:07 hours Thursday because of a
mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
The first plane, a CA 176 plane from Air China, landed at the
airport at 06:47 a.m. today after a more than seven-hour close-up.
</P>
<P>
A MD-11 plane No. 2173 of China Eastern Airlines was found to
have a problem at the front landing chassis shortly after it took
off from Hongqiao Airport in Shanghai for Beijing at 19:38 hours
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Then, the pilots on the plane appealed to return and land at
Hongqiao Airport, and they won approval by the airport control
center.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the plane couldly hardly put down its landing
chasses after two trial landings, and hovered over the airport for
over three hours and eventually made an emergency landing before
fuel was used up.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and twenty passengers aboard, including a crew of
17, were safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
After the accident occurred, leading Party and government
officials including Huang Ju, secretary of the Shanghai Municipal
Committee of the Communist Party of China, Shanghai Mayor Xu
Kuangdi, as well as leaders of the Hongqiao Airport authority and
China Eastern Airlines, arrived promptly at the airport to inspect
the scene.
</P>
<P>
The cause for the accident is under investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
