<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Enacts Cultural Heritage Protection Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council has enacted a Protection and Preservation of
Cultural Heritage Regions Law containing nine chapters, according
to Friday's official newspaper New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was enacted Thursday, is aimed at protecting and
 preserving the cultural heritage that has existed for many years
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The law covers measures to prevent smuggling antiques out of
the cultural heritage regions to foreign countries and to recover
those that have been taken outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Any person who violates this law will be punished with a prison
term of a maximum up to seven years, the law stated.
</P>
<P>
In Myanmar, there are many ancient Buddhist pagodas, temples
and buildings rich with historical and cultural heritage, drawing
attention of world tourists.
</P>
<P>
More than 280 collapsing ancient Buddhist pagodas, temples and
buildings in Myanmar's northwestern Bagan area, 680 kilometres
from Yangon, are being renovated under the aegis of the
government.
</P>
<P>
A total of 890 old pagoda sites throughout the country are also
being excavated and will be rebuilt with original style and taste
of the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is a Buddhist country with 89.4 percent of its
population believing in Buddhism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Develop Electronic Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is launching an
electronic commerce pilot project, which aims to help Thailand
strengthen its position in global trade negotiations, Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said.
</P>
<P>
The country needed to amend existing laws and introduce new
ones in order to make e-commerce a reality, Supachai, who is also
commerce minister, was quoted by Friday's Bangkok Post newspaper
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry has developed a central website --
www.thaiecommerce.net -- which is intended to function as a
central resource with links to the home pages of other businesses.
</P>
<P>
Participation on the site will be limited to Thai businesses
with established brand names or ISO international quality
certification, because the ministry wants to create a good image
for Thai products.
</P>
<P>
The main target export markets under the project are the United
States, the European Union, Japan, the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations and other Asian countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
According to Supachai, the project is part of the government's
attempt to prepare for liberalization of e-commerce worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said there were still obstacles in Thailand to develop
e-commerce, including limited investment in information technology
infrastructure, high service fees, and the reluctance of financial
institutions to support on-line money transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0284 </DOCNO>
