<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Calls For World Bank, IMF Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga, who is also chairperson of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), has called for
reforms of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), saying they are becoming less and less effective.
</P>
<P>
Meeting delegates from South Asian countries to the Second
SAARC Trade fair here Thursday in Colombo, Kumaratunga said the
two institutions are proving less effective in responding
satisfactorily to modern economic challenges, the official Daily
News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the world has changed drastically after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said that international organizations formed 50
years ago in a bipolar world are not effective enough to grapple
with the multifarious problems facing different regions today.
</P>
<P>
They are not seriously geared to face these challenges. She
urged the international community to evolve systems within the
United Nations which will effectively respond to economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga stressed that the SAARC nations should become
economically stronger in order to stand on their own feet and
harmonize their views in world trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
She said, "There is no alternative. We must present a common
view point at the negotiating table to obtain our due. Nothing is
given free. We should not beg any longer."
</P>
<P>
She said SAARC has still not begun to formulate plans to
counter the dominance of the developed world in global trade. It
is still grappling with some problems faced by globalization. A
stronger SAARC raising one voice would hopefully redress these
problems.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC countries with 500 million consumers were until
recently trading mostly with western countries, especially their
former colonialists, ignoring the vast potential of intra-regional
trade, said she, adding that "We are now beginning to explore the
possibilities of increased trade within the SAARC region."
</P>
</TEXT>
