<HEADLINE> Finance Official Calls for Higher Investment Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A Finance Ministry official
has called for higher investment growth during the the later half
year to attain the goal of eight percent growth for China's
economy.
</P>
<P>
"Given the weak export and consumption demand, it is essential
that investment grow 17 percent this year to push economic growth
up to eight percent," said Wang Jiachun, an expert with the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Predicting a turnaround in the national economy for the second
half year, Wang said the government still needs to further
increase investment to realize an eight percent economic growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
That translates to an investment growth of approximately 20
percent for the second half year, when averaged in with the less
than 14 percent growth during the January-June period, Wang
explained.
</P>
<P>
Wang added that China cannot count on help from the export
sector to aid economic growth this year, since the financial
situation in Asia may not improve for the near future.
</P>
<P>
"The ailing Japanese economy, and the more than 100 trillion
Japanese yen in bad loans, will continue to weaken the yen for a
long time to come, and as a result the economic and financial
situation in other Asian countries may even worsen. All these
factors will exert greater pressure on China's exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a major contributor to the national economy, exports made up
about two percent of last year's economic growth. This figure may
diminish to zero this year, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Another major force driving the national economy, consumption
demand, will see no marked increase during the later half year,
which makes high investment demand growth all that more urgent,
according to Wang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
