<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Reaffirms Free Forex Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank has
reiterated that Indonesia would not copy Malaysia's move last week
to impose foreign exchange controls, the Jakarta Post reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril Sabirin said Indonesia had
already had an experience with capital controls in the past and
believed them to be ineffective.
</P>
<P>
"We've already had that experience before and it didn't work
well," he told reporters following a hearing with the House of
Representatives on a new government-proposed banking bill.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia introduced a capital control system in the late 1960s
and early 1970s, a move that created a black market for foreign
currency and rampant currency smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which had been hovering over the 13,000 level to
the U.S. dollar for months, strengthened to about 10,800 last week
before slipping back to the 12,000 level this week in the wake of
widespread demonstrations against the government.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah inched its way to 11,700 against the dollar on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sjahril said that the central bank's release of between 5
million and 15 million U.S. dollars per day to the spot market
partly helped strengthen the local currency.
</P>
<P>
"But these weren't interventions. We're just supplying money
for export and import needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the foreign currency was part of the
international bailout funds provided to Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
