<HEADLINE> Uruguay Increases Trade With Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Uruguay and
Mercosur member countries totaled about 1.56 billion U.S. dollars
in the first half of this year, a 12.6 percent increase over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguay's central bank said the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) has become Uruguay's biggest trading partner, surpassing
the United States and the European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay, the three other
Mercosur member countries, amounted to 800 million dollars out of
Uruguay's total 1.4 billion dollars of exports in the first six
months, while its imports were 763 million dollars from the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the Asian financial crisis, Uruguay's exports to
the region fell 25.5 percent in January-June. To overcome the
adverse effect, Uruguay has expanded its trade with the Mercosur
to cut down its trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, established in 1991, aims at achieving the economic
integration of member states through a free flow of goods and
services between them, the establishment of a common external
tariff, the adoption of common commercial policy and the
coordination of macroeconomic and sectoral policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
