<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smoke Trees in Beijing Blaze Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Visitors to Beijing can
expect to see beautiful " red leaves" at the Fragrant Hill Park
this year thanks to a campaign against seasonal pests in the past
year, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The park attracts domestic and overseas visitors each late
autumn with its charming blazing red leaves on the smoke trees
grown on the 79 ha of hilly lands. Seen from a distance, the hill
looks like it is shrouded by red clouds.
</P>
<P>
But last year, an invasion of Mushi, a mosquito-like insect
with an appetite for smoke tree leaves, left the forest withered,
its beauty gone. Mushi suck the sap from the leaves, shrivelling
them and leaving ugly spots instead of rich greens and reds. The
number of complaints from Fragrant Hills visitors grew.
</P>
<P>
To save the trees, the Beijing Garden Administration and
Fragrant Hills Park (BGAFHP) organized its staff members to kill the
insects. Two roads were built among smoke trees to allow workers
to reach the trees and spray insecticide.
</P>
<P>
Jie Jun, an official with the BGAFHP, attributed the success
of the campaign to a system of sampling 10 fields' pest
populations over the entire smoke tree forest.
</P>
<P>
"Putting of nutritional supplement bars at the roots of 450
comparatively weak smoke trees not only saved them but also ensured
their healthy growth."
</P>
<P>
"This year, we also began to regularly trim off twigs to
increase the sunshine among trees," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0302 </DOCNO>
