<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Head of Italian Anti-State Group Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Former head of the secret P2
Masonic lodge Licio Gelli was arrested Thursday after four months
on the run, Italian Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano said.
</P>
<P>
Gelli, known as "the puppet master", was the most prominent
among 16 members of the P2 Masonic lodge who went on trial in
October 1992 on charges of espionage and conspiracy against the
state.
</P>
<P>
The defendants were acquitted after a 17-month trial, but Gelli
was sentenced in April 1994 to 12 years in prison on lesser
charges of attempting to pervert the course of justice, slandering
magistrates and procuring confidential documents.
</P>
<P>
He absconded in May this year while living under police
surveillance at home in his villa in Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
The 79-year-old Gelli, wearing a false beard and carrying
phoney Italian identity papers, was arrested in Cannes on the
French Riviera in a joint operation by Italian and French police.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Rome, Prime Minister Romano Prodi
hailed the arrest as "very important for Italy."
</P>
<P>
Gelli will be tried in France for using fake identification
card, after which he will be extradited to Italy. Sources in Italy
said Gelli would go to court in Rome in five days following his
extradition.
</P>
<P>
Gelli's sentence had been reduced to eight years on appeal but
he managed to avoid serving any time in prison by virtue of a
further reduction in his sentence.
</P>
<P>
Just before Gelli disappeared, the court of appeal issued a
warrant for Gelli's arrest on charge of fraudulent bankruptcy in
the collapse in 1982 of the Banco Ambrosiano.
</P>
<P>
Gelli joined Fascist Party when he was young. In 1963, he
joined the lodge and established the secret P2 Masonic, which
especially attracts powerful governmental executives as members to
help the lodge's criminal activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
