<HEADLINE> Tianjin Expands Economic Cooperation with Foreign Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest
industrial port city in north China, has accelerated the pace of
investing abroad and attracting overseas funds in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of last year show that Tianjin
enterprises had established 290 firms in Brazil, Singapore,
Germany and Mongolia, with total investments approaching 100
million US dollars. Forty of the firms are engaged in production
and an additional 130 operate in the trade sector. Another ten
firms will be established in various parts of the world during
1998, according to Pi Qiansheng, director of the Municipal
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin Economic Development Zone will join four Egyptian
companies and banks in a cooperative project to build an
experimental industrial zone at the southern tip of the Suez
Canal. The zone will cover 19.4 sq.km. and will be completed at a
cost of 70 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cooperative ventures with foreign firms have proved highly
successful. For example, the Tianjin Tractor Plant invested one
million US dollars in 1995 to construct an assembly line in
Brazil. The company's tractors have hit the market in Brazil and
the plant plans to upgrade technologically to suit local
demand.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime Tianjin has invited overseas investors to
participate in high-tech development projects, restructuring of
state-owned firms and forming joint ventures in travel services
and consulting businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to Pi, the city is currently engaged in negotiations
on 40 foreign-funded projects which will involve estimated
investments of 1.5 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
