<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland, Italy Sign Cooperation Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland signed historic
accords with Italy on justice, immigration and police cooperation
here Thursday, moving closer to the Schengen system of
cross-border cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Swiss Justice Minister Arnold Koller, who signed the three
accords, noted that they were the first that his country had
stipulated with a neighbor. The accords mark the start of a shift
away from centuries of Swiss neutrality in which alliances were
shunned.
</P>
<P>
Koller said he viewed the agreements as "pilot treaties"in the
Alpine nation's new foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, which is not a member of the Schengen Accord, is
negotiating similar agreements with its other neighbors: France,
Germany and Austria.
</P>
<P>
Representing Italy were Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano,
Justice Minister Giovanni Maria Flick and Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini.
</P>
<P>
Napolitano said the immigration accord aimed to "regulate
efforts to combat illegal immigration and the criminal trafficking
of people that is often associated with it".
</P>
<P>
The justice accord provides for better collaboration between
the two countries' judiciaries, especially regarding requests for
evidence located in one country from prosecutors in the other.
</P>
<P>
The third accord established a framework for police cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Initially five European Union members signed an agreement in
the Luxembourg hamlet of Schengen in 1985, aiming to abolish all
border checks on goods and people by 1990. But because of a "lack
of preparation", the Schengen accord had not taken effect until
March 26, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, travellers from EU countries can cross the
borders of any of the signatories without visas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
