<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Cultivate Greenery on Sea Ooze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Common soil plants like
flowers, grass and bushes have been successfully grown on ooze
dredge out of the sea bottom at a 25,000-sq-m experimental garden
in an economic development zone in this North China port city.
</P>
<P>
It is said to be the world's first piece of greenery produced
on saline soil.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, local scientists started to experiment with
a technique to clean salt from sea ooze, using thin plastic tubes.
</P>
<P>
The technique will be used to extend the area of greenery to
two million sq m of saline soil in the zone, which is planned to
cover 33 sq km eventually.
</P>
<P>
Local people used to cover saline soil with cultivated soil in
an effort to plant trees. This kind of mixture, however, became
saline itself within two years.
</P>
<P>
With the new technique, local people have planted trees on
dredged sea ooze covering 20,000 sq m along the coastline, which
is mixed with coal ash and alkaline residue. So far, 90 percent of
the trees have survived, and the quality of soil is improving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Focuses on Counter-Flood Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hubei Province, a grain
producer on China's Yangtze River, is considering its agricultural
production less likely to be severely hurt by the river's flood
season, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"The persistent floods this summer have affected more than 2.54
million ha. of cultivated fields, and destroyed 4.86 million tons
of grain," Duan Wenjie, a provincial agricultural official.
</P>
<P>
A campaign has been launched to minimize agricultural losses in
flood-stricken area, Duan said.
</P>
<P>
By August 20, farmers had pumped water from 233,300 ha. of
fields, and planted 660,600 hectares of late rice and 218,000
ha. of autumn corn and vegetables in "reclaimed fields".
</P>
<P>
According to State Council directions, Hubei will have to
relocate thousands of people living on fields to a "safety belt",
but the farmland there could be still used if approached
scientifically, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
For example, Yanji Town in Ezhou City gave up planting rice
this year on its four ha of fields reclaimed from the river
bank. And the local farmers planted vegetable instead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
