<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Launched to Protect Creditor's Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Courts in South China's
Guangdong Province are taking tougher actions to enforce civil
court orders.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is targeting so-called debt repudiators, people
and enterprises refusing to pay overdue court-ordered debts
despite having the economic ability to do so.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no way for them to escape responsibility
for the debts," said Lu Botao, director of the Guangdong
Provincial Higher People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Initially, names of the repudiators are being published in the
local press in an attempt to bring the problem to the public's
attention.
</P>
<P>
In Foshan, the Intermediate People's Court Publicizes the list
on a large LED (Light-emitting display) bulletin board in downtown
that was once used for commercial advertisements.
</P>
<P>
If the repudiators continue to ignore the court, executors from
the courts may enforce compliance.
</P>
<P>
Local Media have hailed the courts' determination and have
given support to the campaign by publicizing debtors' lists during
the past two months. They described the campaign as "a campaign to
defend the law's honor and to protect legal rights of creditors."
</P>
<P>
Additional support came from the Supreme People's Court which
issued a document last Monday concerning how to deal with the
resistance to execution of laws.
</P>
<P>
"It empowers the local courts with greater authority and
provides practical measures for defending the Law's honor," said
Lu.
</P>
<P>
The tough actions have proven effective in Guangzhou, and
Zhanjiang, Shenzhen, Dongguan and Foshan cities in Guangdong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
