<HEADLINE> Clinton Apologizes to Cabinet Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton apologized to members of his cabinet in a meeting at the
White House on Thursday, urging them to focus on the daily
business of running the country.
</P>
<P>
"It was an extraordinary meeting. It was emotional," Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson told reporters after the meeting. "The
president had a strong message for all us and that was that we
should press ahead with the business of the country."
</P>
<P>
Richardson said, "I support him. He was hurting. He apologized
and we got to move on."
</P>
<P>
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, borrowing from the book
of Galatians, said he told Clinton that "in due season we shall
reap if we do not lose heart."
</P>
<P>
"This is a president who has not lost heart," Slater said.
"This is a Cabinet... that has not lost heart. And that will carry
us through this."
</P>
<P>
Clinton spoke to Senate Democrats earlier in the day, following
a meeting on Wednesday with top Democrats from the House of
Representatives, as he continued his efforts to make amends for
having an affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
and misleading the American people about it.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of healing was done tonight. I think tonight was good; I
think it helped all of us," said Federal Emergency Management
Agency Director James Lee Witt, a longtime friend of Clinton's and
fellow Arkansan.
</P>
<P>
Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner
said most cabinet members at the meeting chose to speak up during
the meeting and each one voiced the desire to continue working for
the American people. "People accepted his apology." she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
