<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delphi Values Aisa-Pacific Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Delphi Automotive Systems
plans to attach greater importance to the Asia-Pacific market in
the wake of its recently announced spin-off from General Motors
(GM) Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Delphi will operate as an independent automobile parts and
components supplier to automakers around the world, rather than
focusing mainly GM's traditional North American market.
</P>
<P>
William Ebbert, president of Delphi's Asia-Pacific Branch, said
here Thursday that the company's sales volume to automakers other
than GM will climb from 38 percent to 50 percent by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, GM and Delphi, a subsidiary of the parent
company, jointly announced that the latter will become a fully
independent publicly traded company in 1999. Delphi is expected to
offer 15-20 percent of its common stock in an initial public
offering during the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ebbert said that Delphi's sales volume in Asia-Pacific region
will grow to 3.4 billion U.S. dollar, or double the 1997
figure. The growth is expected to come largely from sales to other
automakers than GM joint venture plants in the region.
</P>
<P>
Delphi's market share for China will hover between 25-27
percent by the year 2002, up substantially from this year's 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
Marcus Chao, president of Delphi's China Operations, pointed
out that the spin-off from GM will be quite likely to mean that
Delphi will not only be a major supplier of automobile parts and
components for GM's Shanghai joint venture which will turn out its
first vehicles later this year, but will also market products to
all major automobile manufacturers in China, including
Shanghai-Volkswagen, the First Automotive Works, FAW-Volkswagen
and Dongfeng-Citreon.
</P>
<P>
Delphi has invested some 400,000 million U.S. dollars on 15
joint ventures in China. Chao said that Delphi plans to increase
its presence in China, and noted that the country's industrial
policies favor the development of parts and components, rather
than the introduction of new models of automobiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
