<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wenger in Dark over Carlton Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger
said that he was shocked by the news that club is having talks
with media group Carlton Communications.
</P>
<P>
The Highbury board says discussions concern a "range of ways
in which the two companies might work together".
</P>
<P>
Carlton is also talking to Aston Villa - but it is not known
if any takeovers are on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The moves comes after Manchester United accepted a 623m bid
from another broadcaster, BSkyB.
</P>
<P>
Wenger said none of the club's directors had contacted him
about the negotiations with Carlton.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman, who earlier this week voiced his concerns about
giant media corporations taking over the Premiership's top clubs,
said "I can understand the worries of the fans.
</P>
<P>
"Their concern is that the people who own their club should
also love it. They don't want it to just become a business."
</P>
<P>
The former Monaco coach said: "It is the history of football
in England that club owners are in the game for things other than
business reasons, but the game is changing all the time."
</P>
<P>
Wenger, who last season guided Arsenal to their first Double
since 1971, said it would also be very difficult for media firms
to be objective in their dealings with the club they owned.
</P>
<P>
He said there had to be "separation" between the club and the
company that owned it but he gave a sign of hope from France.
</P>
<P>
The television company Canal Plus already owns Paris St
Germain but Wenger said: "When they cover the team's matches they
are more critical of them than any other team." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
