<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Cut by 249 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Dow industrials fell as
much as 345 points Thursday as investors showed their anxiety
about the crises in Washington and the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Bargain hunters provided a late bounce. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 249.48 points to close at 7,615.54,
which is more than 1,700 points, or 18.4 percent, below the July
17 record of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
The drop, combined with Wednesday's 155-point loss, more than
wiped out the record 380 points that the Dow gained Tuesday amid
hopes the Federal Reserve may intervene in the battle against
economic distress spreading around the world.
</P>
<P>
It was the fifth time in just 10 sessions that the Dow has cut
more than 300 points in a day, including the 512-plunge on August
31.
</P>
<P>
In Russia, the ruble and stock market rebounded as a political
crisis neared resolution after President Boris Yeltsin decided to
nominate a compromise candidate for prime minister who is expected
to be approved in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indexes also tumbled Thursday, joining in yet
another global selloff in Brazil and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 26.01 to 980.19, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 39.22 to 1,585.33.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outpaced advancers by a 3-to-1 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to a blistering 875.73 million
shares, rising sharply from Wednesday's tally of 696.94 million.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 12.80 to 487.77, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 7.21 to 606.23.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide rush out of stocks helped push up the market for
U.S. Treasury bonds. The bond rally brought the yield on 30-year
Treasury bills to another all-time low of 5.20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
