<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Cambodian Leaders to Resolve Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday called on Cambodian leaders to resolve their
differences through dialogue and to take measures to prevent
further violence.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman's office, Annan
said he was following very closely and with deep concern the
developments in Cambodia, including the grenade attack on the
residence of Hun Sen, and Sam Raindy's taking refugee in the
Office of the Secretary-General's Personal Representative in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Annan wished to remind the Cambodian authorities of the letter
addressed to him on October 22, 1997 by Ung Huot and Second Prime
Minister Hun Aen, in which they pledged to guarantee the freedom
of political leaders from arrest and detention in respect of acts
and words spoken in connection with political activities relating
to the elections.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, through his Personal Representative in
Cambodia, Lakhan Mehrotra, remains ready to assist Cambodia in
finding a solution acceptable to all and consistent with
democratic practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
