<HEADLINE> U.S. Positive on Nomination of Primakov as Russian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States voiced
cautious optimism on Thursday over the nomination of Yevgeny
Primakov, the acting foreign minister, to become Russia's prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The White House responded positively to President Boris
Yeltsin's nomination earlier on Thursday after the lower house of
parliament, the State Duma, twice rejected his first choice,
Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
"If ratified by the Duma we would expect to have a good and
close working relationship with Prime Minister Primakov," White
House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the United States knows and respects Foreign
Minister Primakov. We've worked closely with him," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
had a "very warm and friendly discussion" by phone, said State
Department spokesman James Rubin at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"She (Albright) indicated she hadn't thought she would be
calling him to congratulate him on being named for such a post
short of being confirmed for such a post," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright and Primakov indicated "They intended to continue to
work as closely as possible together in the future and that they
would be seeing each other in New York at the General Assembly,"
the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed, "Many questions remain to be answered before
we or the Russians themselves have a clear sense of where that
country is heading. Our views will depend on whether they will
keep Russia on the course of reform."
</P>
<P>
As foreign minister, Primakov, 68, was widely seen by the West
as a nationalist, working to restore some of the international
status Moscow lost after the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
He has been criticized in the West for taking a less liberal
line on foreign relations, showing support for Iraq and other
regimes at odds with the West.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, a former Soviet foreign policy expert, is seen as a
technocrat, not ideologically linked to any political faction.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties in Russia's parliament have voiced their
support for Primakov and his nomination is expected to be
confirmed as early as Friday, analysts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
