<HEADLINE> Talks on Romanian-Hungarian Joint Battalion Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Hungarian
Army's General Staff Gen. Col. Ferenc Vegh Thursday ended his
two-day work visit in Romania, after making all necessary
preparations, together with his Romanian counterpart, for the
establishment of the joint Romanian-Hungarian battalion.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting further strengthened the military relations
between the two countries, and we have established again to
continue to be factors that should extend stability in the area,"
Ferenc Vegh said after talks with Constantin Degeratu, chief of
the General Staff of the Romanian Army.
</P>
<P>
According to Ferenc Vegh, this year the two chiefs would meet
again, marking the signing of an agreement on the decision to make
up the joint battalion.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries decided to make up the joint
battalion when their defense ministers met in the Hungarian city
of Debrecen in February 1997. The battalion is due to count 1,000
soldiers -- 500 Romanians and 500 Hungarians. It will carry out
missions of peacekeeping and humanitarian aid in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
