<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Killing of Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday issued a presidential statement, condemning the
"heinous acts" of killing Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Hans Dahlgren, president of the 15-member Security Council,
said in a statement that "members of the Security Council condemn
these heinous acts and violations of international law."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council called for "an urgent investigation into
these crimes, so that perpetrators can be brought to justice," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council extended its welcome to on-going plans for
joint fact-finding missions which involve representatives from
Iran, Pakistan and the United Nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council called on the Taliban, the militant
Islamic Movement that controls most of Afghanistan, to cooperate
fully in ensuring the release and security of remaining diplomats
and other Iranian nationals missing in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also expressed concern over renewed
tension in the region and reiterated the need for the Afghanistan
conflict to be settled in direct negotiations between Afghan
factions, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council called on all concerned to exercise
maximum restraint in this situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council president told reporters that he had
received a phone call from the Iranian Foreign Ministry and a
letter from the Iranian U.N. Mission on the killing of Iranian
diplomats in the neighboring Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami warned Wednesday that his
country would act "in whichever way we see fit" to resolve the
dispute with the Taliban faction.
</P>
<P>
Iran has maintained the buildup of some 70,000 troops and large
stock of military equipment in its border with Afghanistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
