<DOCNO> XIE19980911.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Choice of Primakov, Major Concession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- By nominating Yevgeny Primakov
as prime minister, Russian President Boris Yeltsin made a major
concession under strong pressure from the opposition-dominated
State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The decision, announced Thursday, came after two days of
calculation following the rejection of the original nominee,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, in the Duma in the second balloting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of political standoff between Yeltsin and the
opposition erupted on August 23, when Yeltsin abruptly fired the
five-month-old cabinet of Sergei Kiriyenko and named Chernomyrdin
as premier the next day.
</P>
<P>
The second rejection of Chernomyrdin in the State Duma left
Yeltsin three alternatives. The first choice was to stick to
Chernomyrdin and brace for continued political stalemate with the
State Duma.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the second voting, the four major opposition
factions, the Communists, the People's Power, the Agrarians and
Yabloko, which command 254 of the 450 seats in the State Duma,
said they would continue to shoot down the candidacy if
Chernomyrdin was nominated for a third time, which means
Chernomyrdin stands no chance of getting confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, however, could still appoint Chernomyrdin by decree
and dissolve the State Duma and call early parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Yeltsin was also well aware that an
impeachment commission in the lower house of parliament was
considering the timetable of the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
The opposition left had already indicated that the State Duma
would only consider Chernomyrdin's candidacy after a resolution
was reached on impeachment procedures against the president.
</P>
<P>
When the very existence of the State Duma is at stake, most
deputies would vote for the impeachment procedures. And once the
procedures start, the president would be no longer able to
dissolve the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
The second option, to name Communist deputy Yury Maslyukov, a
former Soviet vice-premier, was no more enviable, because that
would be tantamount to "a government of popular trust" as proposed
by the Communists.
</P>
<P>
A government headed by Maslyukov would pit Yeltsin against both
the cabinet and an opposition-dominated State Duma, a scenario
acceptable to Yeltsin under no circumstances.
</P>
<P>
That left Yeltsin with the third choice -- to nominate Moscow
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov or Acting Foreign Minister Primakov, an
independent.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is seen as the best choice under current conditions
when Russia is riddled with political, economic and social crises.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State Duma, and leaders of
most opposition factions have reacted positively to the Primakov
nomination, which makes it very likely that the career diplomat
will get confirmed in a single balloting.
</P>
<P>
However, observers say, that does not mean an end to the
stalemate between Yeltsin and the State Duma, as new haggling will
emerge in appointment of cabinet members and political and
economic policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
